# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: iec-60320
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] A **19-inch rack** is a standardized frame or enclosure for mounting multiple electronic equipment modules.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Each module has a front panel that is 19 inches (482.6 mm) wide.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] The 19 inch dimension includes the edges or *ears* that protrude from each side of the equipment, allowing the module to be fastened to the rack frame with screws or bolts.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Common uses include computer servers, telecommunications equipment and networking hardware, audiovisual production gear, professional audio equipment, and scientific equipment.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Equipment designed to be placed in a rack is typically described as **rack-mount**/**rack-mountable**, a **rack-mount instrument**, **rack-mounted system**, or **rack-mount chassis**.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] The rack may include subracks or shelves.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] The height of the mountable equipment is standardized as multiples of 1.75 inches (44.45 mm) or one *rack unit* or *U* (less commonly *RU*).
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] The industry-standard rack cabinet is 42U tall; however, many data centers have racks taller than this.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] The term **relay rack** appeared first in the late 19th century, in the world of telephony.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] By 1911, the term was also being used in railroad signaling.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] There is little evidence that the dimensions of these early racks were standardized.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] The 19-inch rack format with rack units of 1.75 inches (44.45 mm) was established as a standard by AT&T around 1922 in order to reduce the space required for repeater and termination equipment in a telephone company central office.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] The earliest repeaters from 1914 were installed in ad hoc fashion on shelves, in wooden boxes and cabinets.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Once serial production started, they were built into custom-made racks, one per repeater.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] But in light of the rapid growth of the toll network, the engineering department of AT&T undertook a systematic redesign, resulting in a family of modular factory-assembled panels all "designed to mount on vertical supports spaced 191⁄2 inches between centers.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] By 1934, it was an established standard with holes tapped for 12-24 screws with alternating spacings of 1.25 inches (31.75 mm) and 0.5 inches (12.70 mm).
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] The 19-inch rack format has remained constant while the technology that is mounted within it has changed considerably and the set of fields to which racks are applied has greatly expanded.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] The 19-inch (482.6 mm) standard rack arrangement is widely used throughout the telecommunications, computing, audio, video, entertainment and other industries, though the Western Electric 23-inch standard, with holes on 1-inch (25.4 mm) centers, is still used in legacy ILEC/CLEC facilities.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Nineteen-inch racks in two-post or four-post form hold most equipment in enterprise data centers, Internet service provider facilities, and professionally designed corporate server rooms, although hyperscale computing typically use wider racks.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] They allow for dense hardware configurations without occupying excessive floor space or requiring shelving.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Nineteen-inch racks are also often used to house professional audio and video equipment, including amplifiers, effects units, interfaces, headphone amplifiers, and even small-scale audio mixers.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] A third common use for rack-mounted equipment is industrial power, control, and automation hardware.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Typically, a piece of equipment being installed has a front panel height 1⁄32 inch (0.031 in; 0.79 mm) less than the allotted number of Us.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Thus, a 1U rackmount computer is not 1.750 inches (44.5 mm) tall but is 1.719 inches (43.7 mm) tall.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] If *n* is the number of rack units, the ideal formula for panel height is *h* = 1.75*n* − 0.031 for calculating in inches, and *h* = 44.45*n* − 0.794 for calculating in millimeters.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] This gap allows a bit of room above and below an installed piece of equipment so it may be removed without binding on the adjacent equipment.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Originally, the mounting holes were tapped with a particular screw thread.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] When rack rails are too thin to tap, rivet nuts or other threaded inserts can be used, and when the particular class of equipment to be mounted is known in advance, some of the holes can be omitted from the mounting rails.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Threaded mounting holes in racks where the equipment is frequently changed are problematic because the threads can be damaged or the mounting screws can break off; both problems render the mounting hole unusable.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Tapping large numbers of holes that may never be used is expensive; nonetheless, tapped-hole racks are still in use, generally for hardware that rarely changes.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Examples include telephone exchanges, network cabling panels, broadcast studios and some government and military applications.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] The tapped-hole rack was first replaced by clearance-hole (Round Hole, Round Unthreaded Holes, and Versa Rail) racks.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] The holes are large enough to permit a bolt to be freely inserted through without binding, and bolts are fastened in place using cage nuts.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] In the event of a nut being stripped out or a bolt breaking, the nut can be easily removed and replaced with a new one.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Production of clearance-hole racks is less expensive.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] The next innovation in rack design has been the square-hole rack.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Square-hole racks allow boltless mounting, such that the rack-mount equipment only needs to insert through and hook down into the lip of the square hole.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Installation and removal of hardware in a square-hole rack is very easy and boltless, where the weight of the equipment and small retention clips are all that is necessary to hold the equipment in place.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Older equipment meant for round-hole or tapped-hole racks can still be used, with the use of cage nuts made for square-hole racks.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Rack-mountable equipment is traditionally mounted by bolting or clipping its front panel to the rack.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Within the IT industry, it is common for network/communications equipment to have multiple mounting positions, including tabletop and wall mounting, so rack-mountable equipment will often feature L-brackets that must be screwed or bolted to the equipment prior to mounting in a 19-inch rack.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] With the prevalence of 23-inch racks in the Telecoms industry, the same practice is also common, but with equipment having 19-inch and 23-inch brackets available, enabling them to be mounted in existing racks.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] A key structural weakness of front-mounted support is the bending stress placed on the mounting brackets of the equipment and the rack itself.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] As a result, 4-post racks have become common, featuring a mirrored pair of rear mounting posts.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Servers and deep pieces of equipment are often mounted using rails that are bolted to the front and rear posts (as above, it is common for such rails to have an adjustable depth), allowing the equipment to be supported by four posts, while also enabling it to be easily installed and removed.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] This, of course, varies by manufacturer, the design of the rack and its purpose, but through common constraining factors (such as raised-floor tile dimensions), these dimensions have become quite common.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] The extra width and depth enable cabling to be routed with ease (also helping to maintain the minimum bend radius for fiber and copper cables) and deeper equipment to be utilized.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] A common feature in IT racks is mounting positions for *zero-U* accessories, such as power distribution units (PDUs) and vertical cable managers and ducts, that utilize the space between the rear rails and the side of the rack enclosure.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] The strength required of the mounting posts means they are invariably not merely flat strips but actually a wider folded strip arranged around the corner of the rack.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] The posts are usually made of steel of around 2 mm thickness (the official standard recommends a minimum of 1.9 mm), or of slightly thicker aluminum.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Racks, especially two-post racks, are often secured to the floor or adjacent building structure so as not to fall over.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] This is usually required by local building codes in seismic zones.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] According to Telcordia Technologies Generic Requirements document GR-63-CORE, during an earthquake, telecommunications equipment is subjected to motions that can over-stress the equipment framework, circuit boards, and connectors.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] The amount of motion and resulting stress depends on the structural characteristics of the building and framework in which the equipment is contained and the severity of the earthquake.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Seismic racks rated according to GR-63, *NEBS Requirements: Physical Protection,* are available, with Zone 4 representing the most demanding environment.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] GR-3108, *Generic Requirements for Network Equipment in the Outside Plant (OSP),* specifies the usable opening of seismic-compliant 19-inch racks.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Heavy equipment or equipment that is commonly accessed for servicing, for which attaching or detaching at all four corners simultaneously would pose a problem, is often not mounted directly onto the rack but instead is mounted via rails (or slides).
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] A pair of rails is mounted directly onto the rack, and the equipment then slides into the rack along the rails, which support it.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] When in place, the equipment may also then be bolted to the rack.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] The rails may also be able to fully support the equipment in a position where it has been slid clear of the rack; this is useful for inspection or maintenance of equipment, which will then be slid back into the rack.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Some rack slides even include a tilt mechanism allowing easy access to the top or bottom of rack-mounted equipment when it is fully extended from the rack.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] A rails kit may include a cable management arm (CMA), which folds the cables attached to the server and allows them to expand neatly when the server is slid out, without being disconnected.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] When there is a large number of computers in a single rack, it is impractical for each one to have its own separate keyboard, mouse, and monitor.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Instead, a KVM switch or LOM software is used to share a single keyboard/video/mouse set amongst many different computers.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Since the mounting hole arrangement is vertically symmetric, it is possible to mount rack-mountable equipment upside-down.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] However, not all equipment is suitable for this type of mounting.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] For instance, most optical disc players will not work upside-down because the driving motor mechanism does not grip the disc.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] A standard 19-inch server rack cabinet is typically 42u in height, 600 millimetres (24 in) wide, and 36 inches (914.40 mm) deep.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] This comprises a volume of 974 L, or just under a cubic meter.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Newer server rack cabinets come with adjustable mounting rails, allowing the user to place the rails at a shorter depth if needed.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] There are a multitude of specialty server racks, including soundproof server racks, air-conditioned server racks, NEMA-rated, seismic-rated, open frame, narrow, and even miniature 19-inch racks for smaller applications.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Cabinets are generally sized to be no wider than the standard 24-inch-wide (610 mm) floor tiles used in most data centers.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Racks carrying telecom equipment like routers and switches often have extra width to accommodate the many cables on the sides.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] 19-inch equipment that needs to be moved often or protected from harsh treatment can be housed in a *road case* approved by the Air Transport Association of America (ATA), sometimes also referred to as a *flight case*.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Road cases typically have plywood sides laminated with polyvinyl chloride (PVC), extruded aluminum edges, steel corners, handles, and latches.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Larger cases typically have wheels for easy transport.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Road case racks come in different heights based on the 1U standard and different depths.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Non-isolated cases simply mount 19-inch mounting posts inside the case.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] To protect equipment from shock and vibration, road rack cases use an inner and outer case.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] These cases can be isolated by thick layers of foam or may use spring-loaded shock mounting.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Touring musicians, theatrical productions and sound and light companies use road case racks.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Rack strips used for road cases come in 2 types: single angle and double angle.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Double-angle rack strips offer better structural strength and an additional mounting face for cable management or additional support for heavy equipment.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] In 1965, a durable fiber-reinforced plastic 19-inch rackmount case was patented by ECS Composites and became widely used in military and commercial applications for electronic deployment and operation.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Rackmount cases are also constructed of thermo-stamped composite, carbon fiber, and DuPont's Kevlar for military and commercial uses.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Portable rack cases using a rotary-molded polyethylene outer shell are a lower-cost alternative to the more durable ATA-approved case.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] These cases are marketed to musicians and entertainers for equipment not subject to frequent transportation and rough handling.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] The polyethylene shell is not fiberglass reinforced and is not rigid.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] The shape of small cases is maintained by the rack rails and the cover seal extrusions alone.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Larger cases are further reinforced with additional plywood or sheet metal.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] The outer shell is frequently embossed in a self-mating pattern to combat the tendency for stacked cases to deform slightly, creating a slope that encourages the upper case to slide off.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] The cases typically use extruded aluminum bands at the ends of the body with tongue-and-groove mating to like bands for the covers.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] End covers are typically secured with either a simple draw latch or a rotary cam *butterfly* latch, named for the shape of the twist handle.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] There is no standard for airflow and cooling of rack-mounted equipment.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] A variety of airflow patterns can be found, including front intakes and rear exhausts, as well as side intakes and exhausts.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Low-wattage devices may not employ active cooling, but use only passive thermal radiation and convection to dissipate heat.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] For rack-mounted computer servers, devices generally intake air on the front and exhaust on the rear.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] This prevents circular airflows where hot exhaust air is recirculated through an adjacent device and causes overheating.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Although open-frame racks are the least expensive, they also expose air-cooled equipment to dust, lint, and other environmental contamination.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] An enclosed sealed cabinet with forced air fans permits air filtration to protect equipment from dust.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Large server rooms will often group rack cabinets together so that racks on both sides of an aisle are either front-facing or rear-facing, which simplifies cooling by supplying cool air to the front of the racks and collecting hot air from the rear of the racks.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] These aisles may themselves be enclosed in a cold air containment tunnel so that cooling air does not travel to other parts of the building where it is not needed or mixes with hot air, making it less efficient.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Raised or false floor cooling in server rooms can serve a similar purpose; they permit cooling airflow to equipment through the underfloor space to the underside of enclosed rack cabinets.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] A difficulty with forced air fan cooling in rack equipment is that fans can fail due to age or dust.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] The fans themselves can be difficult to replace.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] In the case of network equipment, it may be necessary to unplug 50 or more cables from the device, remove the device from the rack, and then disassemble the device chassis to replace the fans.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] However, some rack equipment has been designed to make fan replacement easy, using quick-change fan trays that can be accessed without removing the cabling or the device from the rack, and in some cases without turning off the device so that operation is uninterrupted during replacement.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] A rack's mounting fixture consists of two parallel metal strips (also referred to as *posts* or *panel mounts*) standing vertically.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] The posts are each 0.625 inches (15.88 mm) wide, and are separated by a gap of 17.75 inches (450.85 mm), giving an overall rack width of 19 inches (482.60 mm).
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] The posts have holes in them at regular intervals, with both posts matching, so that each hole is part of a horizontal pair with a center-to-center distance of 18.28–18.34 inches (464.2–465.8 mm).
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] The holes in the posts are arranged vertically in repeating sets of three, with center-to-center separations of 0.5, 0.625, 0.625 inches (12.70, 15.88, 15.88 mm).
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] The hole pattern thus repeats every 1.75 inches (44.45 mm).
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Holes so arranged can either be tapped (usually 10-32 UNF thread, or, less often, 6mm metric) or have square holes for cage nuts.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Racks are vertically divided into regions, 44.45 millimetres (1.75 in) in height.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Each region has three complete hole pairs on each side.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] The holes are centered at 6.35 millimetres (0.25 in), 22.25 millimetres (0.88 in), and 38.1 millimetres (1.50 in) from the top or bottom of the region.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Such a region is commonly known as a **U**, for *unit*, **RU** for *rack unit* or, in German, **HE**, for *Höheneinheit*.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Heights within racks are measured by this unit.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Rack-mountable equipment is usually designed to occupy some integer number of U.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] For example, an oscilloscope might be 4U high.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Rack-mountable computers and servers are mostly between 1U and 4U high.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] A blade server enclosure might require 10U.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Occasionally, one may see fractional U devices, such as a 1.5U server or devices that are just 22.5 or 15 cm in width, allowing for 2 or 3 such devices to be installed side by side, but these are much less common.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] The height of a rack can vary from a few inches, such as in a broadcast console, to a floor-mounted rack whose interior is 45 rack units (200.2 centimetres or 78.82 inches) high.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Many wall-mounted enclosures for industrial equipment use 19-inch racks.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Some telecommunications and networking equipment is available in a narrower 10-inch format with the same unit height as a standard 19-inch rack.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] This standard is also gaining in popularity with hobbyists with limited space at their disposal.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Frames for holding rotary-dial telephone equipment, such as step-by-step telephone switches, were generally 11 feet 6 inches (3.51 m) high.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] A series of studies led to the adoption of frames 7 feet (2.1 m) high, with modular widths in multiples of 1 foot 1 inch (0.33 m)—most often 2 feet 2 inches (0.66 m) wide.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] The **ETSI rack** is defined by the European Telecommunications Standards Institute (ETS 300 119).
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] The distance of the right edge of the right mounting rail to the left edge of the left mounting rail is 535 millimetres (21.1 in).
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] As 535 mm is very close to 21 inches, these racks are sometimes called *21-inch racks*.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] The gap between the posts is 500 millimetres (19.69 in).
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] As 19-inch equipment has a maximum width of 17+1⁄4 inches (438.15 mm), they can easily be mounted in an ETSI rack by means of an ETSI bracket or adapter plate.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] In contrast to the 19-inch standards, ETSI also defined the size of the rack enclosure: the four allowed widths are 150, 300, 600, 900 millimetres (5.9, 11.8, 23.6, 35.4 in) and two allowed depths are 300 and 600 millimetres (12 and 24 in).
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Hole spacing is 25 millimetres (0.98 in).
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] A 23-inch (580 mm) rack is used for housing telephone (primarily), computer, audio and other equipment – although it is less common than the 19-inch rack.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] The size denotes the width of the faceplate for the installed equipment.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] The rack unit is a measure of vertical spacing and is common to both the 19 and 23-inch racks.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Hole spacing is either on 1-inch (25 mm) centers (Western Electric standard), or the same as for 19-inch (482.6 mm) racks (0.625 in or 15.9 mm spacing).
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Open Rack is a mounting system designed by the Open Compute Project that has the same outside dimensions as typical 19-inch racks (e.g., 600 mm width), but internally supports wider equipment modules of 547 millimetres (21.5 in).
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] OpenVPX is an industry standard for modules that can be installed in a chassis in defense applications.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] The modules can provide a variety of functions, similar to equipment in a rack.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Eurorack is a standard generally used in electronic music production to install components of a modular synthesizer, an electronic music instrument.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] This is achieved with a rack mounting system specific to the standard.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Eurocard is an IEEE standard format for printed circuit board (PCB) cards that can be plugged together into a standard chassis, which, in turn, can be mounted in a 19-inch rack.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] The chassis consists of a series of slotted card guides on the top and bottom, into which the cards are slid so they stand on end, like books on a shelf.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] At the spine of each card is one or more connectors which plug into mating connectors on a backplane that closes the rear of the chassis.
[src:iec-60320/19-inch-rack] Several standards such as VMEbus (Versa Module Eurocard bus), STEbus, PCI eXtensions for Instrumentation, openGear and others were developed, which share goals with Eurocard.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] Certification is acquirable for products that have more than 80% energy efficiency at 20%, 50% and 100% of rated load, and a power factor of 0.9 or greater at 100% load.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] The Climate Savers Computing Initiative efficiency level targets for workstations for 2007 through 2011, corresponding to the 80 Plus certification levels.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] From July 2007 through June 2008, the basic 80 Plus level (Energy Star 4.0).
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] For the next year, the target is 80 Plus Bronze level, the following year 80 Plus Silver, then 80 Plus Gold, and finally Platinum.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] For the higher certification levels, the requirement of 0.9 or better power factor was extended to apply to 20% and 50% load levels, as well as at 100% load.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] The Platinum level requires 0.95 or better power factor for servers.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] Redundancy is typically used in data centers.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] Plug Load Solutions tests PSUs according to their testing protocol and lists certified PSUs with downloadable certificates in PDF format, allowing consumers to verify how many and which models are listed by each company.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] There have been instances where companies claim or imply that their supplies are 80 Plus when they have not been certified, and in some cases do not meet the requirements.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] For example, the highest 80 Plus is 80+ Titanium (95.4% efficiency at 50% load).
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] Some companies will claim they meet this requirement even when they are only close (i.e.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] 94.xx%) therefore claiming 80+ Titanium.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] However, this is not the case as one could easily modify the test unit to be more enhanced than production models in order to slightly raise numbers.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] When a company resells an OEM power supply under a new name, it must be certified under the new name and company, even if the OEM supply is certified.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] In some instances, a reseller has claimed a higher wattage than the supply can deliver, so the resellers' supply would not meet 80 Plus requirements.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] Although some power supply manufacturers name their products with similar names, such as "85 Plus", "90 Plus" and "95 Plus", there is no such official certification or standard.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] The efficiency of a computer power supply is its output power divided by its input power; the remaining input power is converted to heat as expected under conservation of energy.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] For instance, a 600 W power supply with 60% efficiency running at full load would draw 1000 W from the mains and waste 400 W as heat.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] A 600 W power supply with 80% efficiency running at full load would draw 750 W from the mains and waste only 150 W as heat.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] For a given power supply, efficiency varies depending on how much power is being delivered.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] Supplies are typically most efficient at between half and three-quarters load, much less efficient at low load, and somewhat less efficient at maximum load.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] Older ATX power supplies were typically 60% to 75% efficient.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] To qualify for 80 Plus, a power supply must achieve at least 80% efficiency at three specified loads (20%, 50% and 100% of maximum rated power).
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] However, 80 Plus supplies may still be less than 80% efficient at lower loads.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] For instance, an 80 Plus, 520 watt supply could still be 70% or less efficient at 60 watts (a typical idle power for a desktop computer).
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] Thus it is still important to select a supply with capacity appropriate to the device being powered.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] It is easier to achieve the higher efficiency levels for higher wattage supplies, so gold and platinum supplies may be less available in consumer-level supplies of reasonable capacity for typical desktop machines.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] Typical computer power supplies may have power factors as low as 0.5 to 0.6.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] The higher power factor reduces the peak current draw, reducing load on the circuit or on an uninterruptible power supply.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] Reducing the heat output of the computer helps reduce noise, since fans do not have to spin as fast to cool the computer.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] Reduced heat and resulting in lower cooling demands may increase computer reliability.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] The testing conditions may give an unrealistic expectation of efficiency for heavily loaded, high power (rated much larger than 300 W) supplies.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] A heavily loaded power supply and the computer it is powering generate significant amounts of heat, which may raise the power supply temperature, which is likely to decrease its efficiency.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] Since power supplies are certified at room temperature, this effect is not taken into account.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] Technically speaking, 80 Plus does test the power supply at full load, under which it is affected by its own heat generation.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] What it does *not* test is the effects of the heat generated by other components in the computer making its way into the power supply.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] There are additional requirements on testing PSUs with cooling fans, which draw power and reduce the measured efficiency.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] PSUs with no fan or an always-on, fixed-speed fan can be tested directly.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] PSUs with an internally-controlled fan must undergo a warmup period of 30 minutes or five fan cycles.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] PSUs with an externally-controlled fan should be tested at minimum fan speed setting.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] 80 Plus does not set efficiency targets for very low load.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] For instance, generation of standby power may still be relatively inefficient, and may not meet requirements of the One Watt Initiative.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] Testing of 80 Plus power supplies shows that they vary considerably in standby efficiency.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] Some power supplies consume half a watt or less in standby with no load, where others consume several times as much at standby, even though they may meet higher 80 Plus certification requirement levels.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] The 80 Plus Titanium level expands requirements to include efficiency at 10% load.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] The 80 Plus Ruby level additionally includes efficiency at 5% load.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] See tables above for precise requirements.
[src:iec-60320/80-plus] The 80 Plus measurement protocol includes the measurement of standby power, but it is not stated anywhere on their webpage whether it is taken account into certification.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] An **AC adapter** or **AC/DC adapter** (also called a **wall charger**, **power adapter**, or informally **wall wart**, or, in some configurations, **power brick**) is a type of external power supply, often enclosed in a case similar to an AC plug.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] AC adapters deliver electric power to devices that lack internal components to draw voltage and power from mains power themselves.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] The internal circuitry of an external power supply is often very similar to the design that would be used for a built-in or internal supply.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] When used with battery-powered equipment, adapters typically charge the battery as well as powering the equipment.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Aside from obviating the need for internal power supplies, adapters offer flexibility: a device can draw power from 120 VAC or 230 VAC mains, vehicle battery, or aircraft battery, just by using different adapters.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Safety can be another advantage, as hazardous 120 or 240 volt mains power is transformed to a lower, safer voltage at the wall outlet before going into the appliance handled by the user.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Size and weight of the device was largely determined by the transformer, which in turn was determined by the power output and mains frequency.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Ratings over a few watts made the devices too large and heavy to be physically supported by a wall outlet.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] The output voltage of these adapters varied with load; for equipment requiring a more stable voltage, linear voltage regulator circuitry was added.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Losses in the transformer and the linear regulator were considerable; efficiency was relatively low, and significant power dissipated as heat even when not driving a load.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Early in the twenty-first century, switched-mode power supplies (SMPSs) became almost ubiquitous for this purpose due to their compact size and light weight relative to their power output ability.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Mains voltage is rectified to a high direct voltage driving a switching circuit, which contains a transformer operating at a high frequency and outputs direct current at the desired voltage.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] The high-frequency ripple is more easily filtered out than mains-frequency.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] The high frequency allows the transformer to be small, which reduces its losses; and the switching regulator can be much more efficient than a linear regulator.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] The result is a much more efficient, smaller, and lighter device.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Safety is ensured, as in the older linear circuit, because a transformer still provides galvanic isolation.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Many inexpensive switched-mode AC adapters do not implement adequate filtering and/or shielding for electromagnetic interference that they generate.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] The nature of these high speed, high-energy switching designs is such that when these preventative measures are not implemented, relatively high energy harmonics can be generated, and radiated, well into the radio portion of the spectrum.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] The amount of RF energy typically decreases with frequency; so, for instance, interference in the medium wave (US AM) broadcast band in the one megahertz region may be strong, while interference with the FM broadcast band around 100 megahertz may be considerably less.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Distance is a factor; the closer the interference is to a radio receiver, the more intense it will be.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Even WiFi reception in the gigahertz range can be degraded if the receiving antennae are very close to a radiating AC adapter.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] A determination of if interference is coming from a specific AC adapter can be made simply by unplugging the suspect adapter while observing the amount of interference received in the problem radio band.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] In a modern household or business environment, there may be multiple AC adapters in use; in such a case, unplug them all, then plug them back in one by one until the culprit or culprits is found.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Traditionally, wall adapters provided a constant voltage.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Later, battery charging protocols such as Quick Charge by Qualcomm and USB Power Delivery started allowing charged devices to request different voltages suited for their needs, usually higher voltages to increase power without adding heat to the copper wires of the USB cable.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] In the past, "SuperCharge" by Huawei and "Dash Charge" by OnePlus did the opposite, requesting a slightly lowered voltage to directly match the battery voltage inside the smartphone so no change of voltage has to take place inside the phone, leading to less heating up.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] This required special USB cables with thicker copper wires.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] In the early 2020s, the use of gallium nitride instead of silicon in switching wall adapters bumped up their output power at the same physical size, making compact wall warts able to power even some laptops, not only smartphones and tablet computers.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] The creation of Gallium Nitride chargers was delayed owing to their excessive costs and that fast charging technology was less in demand than it has become after 2020.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] External AC adapters are widely used to power small or portable electronic devices.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] A survey of consumers showed widespread dissatisfaction with the cost, inconvenience, and wastefulness of the profusion of power adapters used by electronic devices.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] The issue of inefficiency of some power supplies has become well known, with U.S. president George W.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Bush referring in 2001 to such devices as "energy vampires".
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Legislation is being enacted in the EU and a number of U.S. states to reduce the level of energy wasted by some of these devices.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Such initiatives include standby power and the One Watt Initiative.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] But others have argued that these inefficient devices are low-powered, e.g., devices that are used for small battery chargers, so even if they have a low efficiency, the amount of energy they waste is less than 1% of household consumption of electric energy.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Considering the total efficiency of power supplies for small electronic equipment, the older mains-frequency linear transformer-based power supply was found in a 2002 report to have efficiencies from 20 to 75%, and have considerable energy loss even when powered up but not supplying power.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Switched-mode power supplies (SMPSs) are much more efficient; a good design can be 80–90% efficient, and is also much smaller and lighter.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] In 2002 most external plug-in "wall wart" power adapters commonly used for low-power consumer electronics devices were of linear design, as well as supplies built into some equipment.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] External supplies are usually left plugged in even when not in use, and consume from a few watts to 35 watts of power in that state.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Since the report was published, SMPSs have indeed replaced linear supplies to a great extent, even in wall warts.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] The 2002 report estimated that 6% of electrical energy used in the U.S.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] "flows through" power supplies (not counting only the wall warts).
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] The website where the report was published said in 2010 that despite the spread of SMPSs, "today's power supplies consume at least 2% of all U.S. electricity production.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] More efficient power supply designs could cut that usage in half".
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Since wasted electrical energy is released as heat, an inefficient power supply is hot to the touch, as is one that wastes power without an electrical load.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] This waste heat is itself a problem in warm weather, since it may require additional air conditioning to prevent overheating, and even to remove the unwanted heat from large supplies.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] External power adapters can fail, or can become separated from the product they are intended to power.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Consequently, there is a market for replacement adapters.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] The replacement must match input and output voltages, match or exceed current capability, and be fitted with a matching connector.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Many electrical products are poorly labeled with information concerning the power supply they require, so it is prudent to record the specifications of the original power supply in advance, to ease replacement if the original is later lost.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Careful labeling of power adapters can also reduce the likelihood of a mixup which could cause equipment damage.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Some "universal" replacement power supplies allow output voltage and polarity to be switched to match a range of equipment.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] With the advent of switch-mode supplies, adapters which can work with any voltage from 110 VAC to 240 VAC became widely available; previously either 100–120 VAC or 200–240 VAC versions were used.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Adapters which can also be used with motor vehicle and aircraft power *(see EmPower)* are available.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Four-way **X connectors** or six-way **star connectors**, also known as **spider connectors**, with multiple plug sizes and types are common on generic power supplies.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Other replacement power supplies have arrangements for changing the power connector, with four to nine different alternatives available when purchased in a set.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] This allows many different configurations of AC adapters to be put together, without requiring soldering.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Philmore and other competing brands offer similar AC adapters with interchangeable connectors.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] The label on a power supply may not be a reliable guide to the actual voltage it supplies under varying conditions.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Many low-cost power supplies are "unregulated", in that their voltage can change considerably with load.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] If they are lightly loaded, they may put out much more than the nominal "name plate" voltage, which could damage the load.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] If they are heavily loaded, the output voltage may droop appreciably, in some cases well below the nominal label voltage even within the nominal rated current, causing the equipment being supplied to malfunction or be damaged.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Supplies with linear (as against switched) regulators are heavy, bulky, and expensive.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Modern switched-mode power supplies (SMPSs) are smaller, lighter, and more efficient.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] They put out a much more constant voltage than unregulated supplies as the input voltage and the load current vary.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] When introduced, their prices were high, but by the early 21st century the prices of switch-mode components had dropped to a degree which allowed even cheap supplies to use this technology, saving the cost of a larger and heavier mains-frequency transformer.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Some universal adapters automatically set their output voltage and maximum current according to which of a range of interchangeable tips is fitted; tips are available to fit and supply appropriate power to many notebook computers and mobile devices.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Different tips may use the same connector, but automatically supply different power; it is essential to use the right tip for the apparatus being powered, but no switch needs to be set correctly by the user.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] The advent of switch-mode power supplies has allowed adapters to work from any AC mains supply from 100 to 240 V with an appropriate plug; operation from standard 12 V DC vehicle and aircraft supplies can also be supported.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] With the appropriate adapter, accessories, and tips, a variety of equipment can be powered from almost any source of power.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] A battery eliminator is an adapter intended to allow a device intended for battery operation, such as a radio, to be operated from an AC outlet.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] All radios, except crystal sets, used inconvenient and messy vacuum tube batteries until the mid- to late-1920s.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Battery eliminators that plugged into light sockets became very popular.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Early commercial units were produced by the Edward S.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Rogers, Sr. company in 1925 as a complement to its line of batteryless radios.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Another early producer of battery eliminators was the Galvin Manufacturing Corporation (later known as Motorola), which was opened on September 25, 1928, by Paul Galvin and his brother Joseph E.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Eliminators became obsolete for radios after RCA introduced AC tubes in 1927, enabling receivers to plug into household power.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] The industry rapidly adopted AC tubes, and companies which launched exclusively manufacture that product such as Philco had to quickly pivot to radio manufacturing to remain relevant and existent.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] In early laptop computers, the power supply units were internal like in desktop computers.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] To facilitate portability by sparing physical space and reducing the weight, power supply units were externalized.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] When a laptop computer is operated while recharging, the integrated circuitry which controls the charging makes use of a power supply unit's remaining electrical current capacity.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] This allows supplying the device's components with power during usage while maintaining an uncompromised constant charging speed.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] The USB connector (and voltage) has emerged as a de facto standard in low-power AC adapters for many portable devices.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] In addition to serial digital data exchange, the USB standard also provides 5 VDC power, up to 500 mA (900 mA over USB 3.0).
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Numerous accessory gadgets ("USB decorations") were designed to connect to USB only for DC power and not for data interchange.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] The USB Implementers Forum in March, 2007 released the USB Battery Charging Specification which defines, "...limits as well as detection, control and reporting mechanisms to permit devices to draw current in excess of the USB 2.0 specification for charging ...".
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Electric fans, lamps, alarms, coffee warmers, battery chargers, and even toys have been designed to tap power from a USB connector.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Plug-in adapters equipped with USB receptacles are widely available to convert 120 VAC or 240 VAC power or 12 VDC automotive power to 5 VDC USB power (see photo at right).
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] The trend towards more-compact electronic devices has driven a shift towards the micro-USB and mini-USB connectors, which are electrically compatible in function to the original USB connector but physically smaller.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] In 2012, a USB Power Delivery Specification was proposed to standardize delivery of up to 100 watts (increased to 240 W in 2021), suitable for devices such as laptop computers that usually depend on proprietary adapters.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] The ITU published Recommendation ITU-T L.1000, "Universal power adapter and charger solution for mobile terminals and other hand-held ICT devices", which specifies a charger similar in most respects to that of the GSMA/OMTP proposal and to the European Common external power supply.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] The ITU recommendation was expanded and updated in June, 2011.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] The hope is to markedly reduce the profusion of non-interchangeable power adapters.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] The European Union defined a Common external power supply for "hand-held data-enabled mobile phones" (smartphones) sold from 2010, intended to replace the many incompatible proprietary power supplies and eliminate waste by reducing the total number of supplies manufactured.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] Conformant supplies deliver 5 VDC via a micro-USB connector, with preferred input voltage handled ranging from 90 to 264 VAC.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] In 2006 Larry Page, a founder of Google, proposed a 12 V and up to 15 A standard for almost all equipment requiring an external converter, with new buildings fitted with 12 VDC wiring, making external AC-to-DC adapter circuitry unnecessary.
[src:iec-60320/ac-adapter] IEC has created a standard for interchangeable laptop power supplies, IEC 62700 (full name "IEC Technical Specification 62700: DC Power supply for notebook computer"), which was published on February 6, 2014.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and sockets may sometimes combine male and female contacts.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and wall-mounted sockets for portable appliances became available in the 1880s, to replace connections to light sockets.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A proliferation of types were subsequently developed for both convenience and protection from electrical injury.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Electrical plugs and sockets differ from one another in voltage and current rating, shape, size, and connector type.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Different standard systems of plugs and sockets are used around the world, and many obsolete socket types are still found in older buildings.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Coordination of technical standards has allowed some types of plug to be used across large regions to facilitate the production and import of electrical appliances and for the convenience of travellers.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some multi-standard sockets allow use of several types of plug.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Incompatible sockets and plugs may be used with the help of adaptors, though these may not always provide full safety and performance.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Single-phase sockets have receptacles for two power pins, one to carry the electrical current from the power source to the connected device (called *live*, *line*, or *phase pin*) and another one to carry it back to the power source (called *neutral pin*).
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Many sockets have a third receptacle or pin for a safety connection to earth ground.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The plug is a *male* connector, usually with protruding pins that match the receptacles (*female* contacts) in a socket.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some plugs also have a female contact, used only for the earth ground connection.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Typically no energy is supplied to any exposed pins or terminals on the socket, hence the power pins are always part of the plug rather than the socket.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In addition to the recessed contacts of the energised socket, plug and socket systems often have other safety features to reduce the risk of electric shock or damage to appliances.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] When commercial electric power was first introduced in the 1880s, it was used primarily for lighting.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Other portable appliances (such as vacuum cleaners, electric fans, smoothing irons, and curling-tong heaters) were connected to light-bulb sockets.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] As early as 1885 a two-pin plug and wall socket format was available on the British market.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] By about 1910 the first three-pin earthed (grounded) plugs appeared.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Over time other safety improvements were gradually introduced to the market.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] One of the first national standards for plugs and wall sockets was enacted in 1915 in the UK.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Designs of plugs and sockets have gradually developed to reduce the risk of electric shock and fire.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs are shaped to prevent bodily contact with live parts.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets may be recessed and plugs designed to fit closely within the recess to reduce risk of a user contacting the live pins.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Contact pins may be sheathed with insulation over part of their length, so as to reduce exposure of energized metal during insertion or removal of the plug.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets may have automatic shutters to stop foreign objects from being inserted into energized contacts.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sockets are often set into a surround which prevents accidental contact with the live wires in the wall behind it.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some also have an integrated cover (e.g. a hinged flap) covering the socket itself when not in use, or a switch to turn off the socket.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some plugs, particularly the British Type G, have a built-in fuse which breaks the circuit if too much current flows.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A third contact for a connection to earth is intended to protect against insulation failure of the connected device.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some early unearthed plug and socket types were revised to include an earthing pin or phased out in favour of earthed types.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The plug is often designed so that the earth ground contact connects before the energized circuit contacts.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The assigned IEC appliance class is governed by the requirement for earthing or equivalent protection.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Class I equipment requires an earth contact in the plug and socket, while Class II equipment is unearthed and protects the user with double insulation.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Where a "neutral" conductor exists in supply wiring, polarization of the plug can improve safety by preserving the distinction in the equipment.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] For example, appliances may ensure that switches interrupt the live side of the circuit, or can connect the shell of a screw-base lampholder to neutral to reduce electric shock hazard.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some designs, polarized plugs cannot be mated with non-polarized sockets.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In most NEMA 1 plugs, for example, the neutral blade is slightly wider than the hot blade, so it can only be inserted one way.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Wiring systems where both circuit conductors have a significant potential with respect to earth do not benefit from polarized plugs.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Plugs and power cords have a rated voltage and current assigned to them by the manufacturer.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Using a plug or power cord that is inappropriate for the load may be a safety hazard.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] For example, high-current equipment can cause a fire when plugged into an extension cord with a current rating lower than necessary.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Sometimes the cords used to plug in dual voltage 120 V / 240 V equipment are rated only for 125 V, so care must be taken by travellers to use only cords with an appropriate voltage rating.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Various methods can be used to increase the number or reach of sockets.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Extension cords (extension leads) are used for temporary connections when a socket is not within convenient reach of an appliance's power lead.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This may be in the form of a single socket on a flexible cable or a power strip with multiple sockets.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A power strip may also have switches, surge voltage protection, or overcurrent protection.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Multisocket adaptors (or "splitters") allow the connection of two or more plugs to a single socket.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] They are manufactured in various configurations, depending on the country and the region in which they are used, with various ratings.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This allows connecting more than one electrical consumer item to one single socket and is mainly used for low power devices (TV sets, table lamps, computers, etc.).
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] They are usually rated for 6 A, 10 A, or 16 A at 250 V or for 15 A or less at 125 V.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some countries such adaptors are banned and are not available in shops, as they may lead to fires due to overloading them or can cause excessive mechanical stress to wall-mounted sockets.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors can be made with ceramic, Bakelite, or other plastic bodies.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] but is intended to accept a number of different plug types.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Old Chinese dual socket accepting both unearthed two-pin (upper) and earthed three-pin (lower) plugs.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] "Hybrid", "multi-standard", or "universal" sockets are intended to accommodate plugs of two or more types.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] In some jurisdictions, they violate safety standards for sockets.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Safety advocates, the United States Army, and a manufacturer of sockets point out a number of safety issues with universal socket and adaptors, including voltage mismatch, exposure of live pins, lack of proper earth ground connection, or lack of protection from overload or short circuit.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Universal sockets may not meet technical standards for durability, plug retention force, temperature rise of components, or other performance requirements, as they are outside the scope of national and international technical standards.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A technical standard may include compatibility of a socket with more than one form of plug.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] The Thai dual socket is specified in figure 4 of TIS 166-2549 and is designed to accept Thai plugs, and also Type A, B, and C plugs.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Chinese dual sockets have both an unearthed socket that accepts A and C plugs and an earthed socket that accepts Type I plugs.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Since the 2021 revision of the Chinese standard, the installation of such dual sockets is no longer allowed in China, but they can still be found in many existing installations.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Such Thai or Chinese dual sockets also accept plugs normally fitted to 120 V appliances (e.g.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] 120 V rated NEMA 1-15 ungrounded plugs).
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] This can cause an electrical incompatibility, since both countries supply residential power at 220–230 V.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] These dual sockets also accept French and Schuko plugs (Types E and F), but unsafely: no earth contact is established and live pins may be exposed when a plug is partially inserted.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Commonly, manufacturers provide an IEC 60320 inlet on an appliance, with a detachable power cord (mains flex lead) and appropriate plug in order to avoid manufacturing whole appliances, with the only difference being the type of plug.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Alternatively, the plug itself can often be swappable using standard or proprietary connectors.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors between standards are not included in most standards, and as a result they have no formal quality criteria defined.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Physical compatibility does not ensure that the appliance and socket match in frequency or voltage.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Adaptors allow travellers to connect devices to foreign sockets, but do not change voltage or frequency.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] A voltage converter is required for electrical compatibility in places with a different voltage than the device is designed for.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Mismatch in frequency between supply and appliances may still cause problems even at the correct voltage.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Some appliances have a switch for the selection of voltage.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p01] Many modern devices use AC adapters that accept 100–240 V voltage at 50 or 60 Hz, meaning they can be used anywhere in the world as long as a suitable plug adapter is used.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs and sockets used in a given area are regulated by local governments.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) maintains a guide with letter designations for generally compatible types of plugs, which expands on earlier guides published by the United States Department of Commerce.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This is a *de facto* naming standard and guide to travellers.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some letter types correspond to several current ratings or different technical standards, so the letter does not uniquely identify a plug and socket within the type family, nor guarantee compatibility.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Physical compatibility of the plug and socket does not ensure correct voltage, frequency, or current capacity.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Not all plug and socket families have letters in the IEC guide, but those that have are noted in this article, as are some additional letters commonly used by retail vendors.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Europe, CENELEC publishes a list of approved plug and socket technical standards used in the member countries.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A number of countries in Oceania as well as China and Argentina use a plug that has two flat pins at an angle, forming a V-shape, as well as a flat vertical grounding pin.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While the exact pin dimensions and the polarity vary between different countries, these plugs and sockets are all compatible with each other and are known as *Type I*.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket system used in Argentina is defined by several standards of the Argentine Normalization and Certification Institute (IRAM).
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] IRAM 2071 defines two sockets that have the same form factor, but differ in size and rating.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The smaller, more common socket is rated for 10 A.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The larger variant, rated for 20 A, is mostly used for higher-power appliances such as air conditioners.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] IRAM 2073 defines the corresponding plugs used for Class I appliances (that require earthing).
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket system has an earthing pin and two flat current-carrying pins forming an inverted V-shape (120°).
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The power pins are set at 30° to the vertical with a distance of 7.92 mm (0.312 in) from their centres to the centre of the plug; they are 18.2 mm (0.717 in) long.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earthing pin is 21.4 mm (0.843 in) long and placed below the plug centre at a distance of 10.31 mm (0.406 in).
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins of the 20 A version are larger – 8.0 by 1.9 mm (0.315 by 0.075 in) – and placed further away from the centre of the plug – 9.53 mm (0.375 in) for the power pins, 11.1 mm (0.437 in) for the earthing pin.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] At 21.8 mm (0.858 in), the earthing pin is a bit longer, while the power pins are a bit shorter at 17.8 mm (0.701 in).
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is also an unearthed version of the 10 A plug, defined by IRAM 2063, that lacks an earthing pin and can be used with Class II appliances.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A plugs, on the other hand, must always provide earthing.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Insulating sleeves around the upper parts of the power pins are allowed, but not required.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] When used, they significantly reduce the risk of electric shock from accidentally touching the pins of a partially inserted plug.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Because the pins of the 20 A plug are placed farther apart than those of the 10 A plug, the two Argentine plug types are mutually incompatible.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is not possible to insert a 20 A plug into a 10 A socket or vice versa.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The most important difference from the Australasian and Chinese plugs is that the Argentine plug is wired with the live and neutral contacts reversed.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Argentina, when the earth contact is positioned downward, the live (line) contact is on the right side of the socket, while in Australasia and China it is on the left (assuming the same orientation).
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Brazil, Type I–style plugs and sockets are still commonly used in old installations for high-power appliances like air conditioners, dishwashers, and household ovens.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are often called "Argentine plugs" and are indeed physically identical to the IRAM plugs rated for 20 A, though they might have been developed independently on the basis of the American NEMA 10-20 standard (which uses the same form factor).
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While these plugs are sometimes used for normal single-phase power and wired in the same way as in Argentina, some are wired for split-phase power with two "hot" (or phase) wires and a neutral wire, but no earth connection.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Care must therefore be taken that the same wiring scheme is used in the socket and in the plug, since otherwise the equipment would surely be damaged.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In newer installations, the 20 A version of the Type N plug, adopted by Brazil as national standard NBR 14136, is generally preferred.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This Australian/New Zealand standard is used in Australia, New Zealand, Fiji, Tonga, Solomon Islands, and Papua New Guinea.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug shape and basic dimensions are identical to the 10 A plug used in Argentina.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Australasian standard defines a series of plugs and sockets for devices drawing up to 10, 15, 20, 25 and 32 A that are one-way compatible.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] All sockets accept plugs of equal or lower current ratings, but not higher.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] For example, a 10 A plug will fit all sockets but a 20 A plug will fit only 20, 25 and 32 A sockets.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The three flat pins all measure 6.35 by 1.63 mm (0.250 by 0.064 in) – very slightly larger than in Argentina.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The length of the power pins is 17.06 mm (0.672 in), while the earthing pin has a length of 19.94 mm (0.785 in) – somewhat shorter than in Argentina.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 15 A plug, the height of the earth pin is increased from 6.35 to 9.08 mm (0.357 in), while the dimensions of the power pins remain the same.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 20 A plug, however, their height is increased in the same way, so that the surface dimensions of the three pins are again identical.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the 25 A version, the earthing pin takes the shape of an inverted L (an extra bar is added at the top end), and in the 32 A version it takes the shape of a sideways U (extra bars are added at both ends).
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In general, only 10 A and 15 A socket outlets are likely to be encountered in domestic or commercial installations.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A sockets are rare and higher rated ones are very rare.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] An unearthed version of the 10 A plug with two angled power pins but no earthing pin is used with double-insulated appliances, but sockets and higher-rated plugs always include an earth contact.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In New Zealand, PDL 940 "tap-on" or "piggy-back" plugs are available which allow a second 10 A plug to be fitted to the rear of the plug.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Australia these piggy-back plugs are now available only on pre-made extension leads.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A novel feature of modern Australian socket outlets is a snap-fitting surround for the socket, covering the screws that affix the socket to the wall, and extending all the way around the socket periphery.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Australia's standard plug/socket system was originally codified as standard C112 (floated provisionally in 1937, and adopted as a formal standard in 1938), which was based on a design patented by Harvey Hubbell and was superseded by AS 3112 in 1990.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The requirement for insulated pins was introduced in the 2000 revision, and became effective 5 years after its publication.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard for Mainland Chinese plugs and sockets (excluding Hong Kong and Macau) is set out in GB 2099.1 and GB 1002.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] As part of China's commitment for entry into the WTO, the new CPCS (Compulsory Product Certification System) has been introduced, and compliant Chinese plugs have been awarded the CCC Mark by this system.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs are three-wire, earthed, rated for 10 or 16 A, 250 V, and are chiefly used for Class I applications.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins of the 10 A version are 1.55 mm (0.061 in) thick by 6.4 mm (0.252 in) wide; the centres of the power pins are placed 7.9 mm (0.311 in) from the plug centre, while the centre of the earth pin is 10.3 mm (0.406 in) away.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In both plug types, the live and neutral pins are 18 mm (0.709 in) long, while the earth pin is 21 mm (0.827 in) long.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This makes the 10 A version compatible with Argentine and Australasian 10 A sockets, as their dimensions are nearly identical.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Except for the pin length, all dimensions of the 16 A version are slightly larger.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Its pins are 1.8 by 8.1 mm (0.071 by 0.319 in); the centres of the power pins are placed 9.5 mm (0.374 in) from the plug centre, while the centre of the earth pin is 11.1 mm (0.437 in) away.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This makes this plug compatible with the 20 A sockets used in Argentina.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is, however, incompatible with Chinese 10 A sockets as well as all Australasian sockets because of the different pin spacing.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some sockets in China include a physical lockout preventing access to the active and neutral terminals unless an earth pin (which is slightly longer than the other two pins) is entered first; others require pins to be inserted into both live terminals to open the shutter.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since its 2024 revision, GB 1002 also defines unearthed two-pin Class II plugs, though such plugs cannot be inserted into sockets that require an earth pin to open the shutters.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Already since 2008 for 16 A, and since 2021 also for 10 A, there is an unearthed Class II plug variant that uses an unwired dummy earth pin to open the shutters; unearthed plugs of this kind fit into all Chinese sockets of the same rating.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] China also uses American/Japanese NEMA 1-15 sockets and plugs for Class II appliances (however, polarized plugs with one prong wider than the other are not accepted).
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older versions of GB 1002 also defined a socket type that accepts Europlugs (Type C), but this hybrid socket was removed from the 2021 revision of the standard.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The voltage at a Chinese socket of any type is 220 V.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In China, sockets typically have the earth contact above the power pins, while in Argentina and Australasia it is usually positioned below them.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While Australasian plugs have insulating sleeves around the upper part of their power pins, that is not the case for most existing Chinese plugs, hence their pins may become live while there is still a large enough gap between the faces of the plug and socket to allow a finger to touch the pin.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since 2022, insulating sleeves are also allowed on plugs sold in China; they will be mandatory from 2027.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The polarity of all grounded British sockets is standardized: earth is at the top and live is at the right of the socket.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This convention is also followed in other countries using these plugs and sockets.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 546, "Two-pole and earthing-pin plugs, socket-outlets and socket-outlet adaptors for AC (50-60 Hz) circuits up to 250 V" describes four sizes of plug rated at 2 A, 5 A (Type D), 15 A (Type M) and 30 A.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs have three round pins arranged in a triangle, with the larger top pin being the earthing pin.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Plugs are non-interchangeable between current ratings.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Introduced in 1934, the BS 546 type has mostly been displaced in the UK by the BS 1363 standard.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] According to the IEC, some 40 countries use Type D (among them India) and about 15 countries use Type M.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 1363 "13 A plugs, socket-outlets, adaptors and connection units" is the main plug and socket type used in the United Kingdom.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] According to the IEC it is also used in over 50 countries worldwide.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some of these countries have national standards based on BS 1363, including Bahrain, Hong Kong, Ireland, Cyprus, Macau, Malaysia, Malta, Saudi Arabia, Singapore, Brunei, Sri Lanka, and the UAE.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This plug has three rectangular pins forming an isosceles triangle.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The BS 1363 plug has a fuse rated to protect its flexible cord from overload and consequent fire risk.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Modern appliances may only be sold with a fuse of the appropriate size pre-installed.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The United Kingdom, Ireland, and Malta use the BS 4573 two-pin plug and socket for electric shavers and toothbrushes.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has insulating sleeves on the pins.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Although similar to the Europlug Type C, the diameter and spacing of the pins are slightly different and hence it will not fit into a Schuko socket.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are, however, two-pin sockets and adaptors which will accept both BS 4573 and Europlugs.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The **CEE 7** standard is a set of general specifications and standard sheets for AC plugs and sockets, first created by the IECEE standards body in 1951.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] They are now the main system in use in most of Europe.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7 incorporates the two round pinned (with centres spaced at 19 mm) Schuko or Type F plug that was patented by Siemens-Schuckertwerke in 1929, and also the Type E plug, likely developed in Belgium around 1930 but never patented, therefore adopted by Czecho­slovakia, Poland and France.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7 have also developed and incorporated "universal" plugs that will work on both Type E and Type F sockets such as the Europlug.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] European countries (whether EU or non-EU) each have their own regulations and national standards; for example, some require child-resistant shutters, while others do not.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CE marking is neither applicable nor permitted on plugs and sockets.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7 system has been adapted in many countries outside of Europe as well.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/1 sockets and CEE 7/2 plugs are 2-pole connectors rated 10/16 A up to 250 V, with 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in) pins.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It has no protective earth and therefore poses a risk of electric shock due to missing circular recess.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Their sale or use has been banned in a number of countries.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/3 socket and CEE 7/4 plug are commonly called *Schuko*, an abbreviation for *Schutzkontakt*, *Protective contact* to earth ("Schuko" itself is a registered trademark of a German association established to own the term).
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The socket has a circular recess with two round holes and two earthing clips that engage before live pin contact is made.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Schuko system is unpolarized, allowing live and neutral to be reversed.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is used in most European countries and on other continents, including in South Korea and Uruguay.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The European countries not using it at all are Belgium, Czech Republic, Cyprus, Ireland, Liechtenstein, Malta, Switzerland, and the United Kingdom; those not using it predominantly are Denmark, Faroe Islands, France, Italy, Monaco, San Marino, and Slovakia.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This electrical connector most likely originated in Belgium, where it was introduced in the 1930s by Vynckier Frères as well as Niko.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/5 socket and CEE 7/6 plug are defined in several national standards, among them the Belgian NBN C 61‑112, the French NF C 61-314, and the Czech ČSN 35 4516.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/5 socket is in Europe the primary standard of Belgium, Czechia, France, Poland, and Slovakia.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Denmark including the Faroe Islands and Greenland, both CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 are nowadays explicitly allowed alongside Type K.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The socket has a circular recess with two round holes.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The round earth pin projecting from the socket connects before the energized contacts touch.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earth pin is centred between the apertures, offset by 10 mm (0.394 in).
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has two round pins measuring 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in), spaced 19 mm (0.748 in) apart and with an aperture for the socket's projecting earth pin.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/7 plugs have been designed to solve this incompatibility by being able to fit in either type of socket.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is rated at 16 A and looks similar to CEE 7/4 plugs, but with earth contacts to fit both CEE 7/5 and CEE 7/3 sockets.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Due to its compatibility with the inherently unpolarized Schuko (CEE 7/4) plugs, appliances using it cannot expect the current to flow in any particular direction.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The CEE 7/16 Alternative I unearthed plug is used for unearthed appliances.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Alternative I is a round plug with cutouts to make it compatible with CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] (The similar-appearing CEE 7/17 has larger pins and a higher current rating.) This alternative is seldom used.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Alternative II, popularly known as the Europlug, is a flat 2.5 A-rated plug with two round 4 by 19 mm (0.157 by 0.748 in) pins, defined by Cenelec standard EN 50075 and national equivalents.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Europlug is not rewirable and must be supplied with a flexible cord.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It can be inserted in either direction, so live and neutral are connected arbitrarily.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] To improve contact with socket parts the Europlug has slightly flexible pins which converge toward their free ends.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Europlug is widely used in most of Europe and parts of the Middle East, Africa, South America, and Asia.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is no socket defined to accept only the Europlug.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Instead, it fits a range of sockets including all three CEE 7 sockets (unearthed, German/"Schuko", and Belgian/French) and also many non-CEE 7 standard sockets such as Swiss, Danish and Italian (10 A) ones as well as Israeli sockets.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] British shaver sockets also accept Europlugs, although in this configuration the connection supply is only rated at 200 mA.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This is a round plug compatible with all three types of CEE 7 sockets.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also called the "contour plug", it has two round pins measuring 4.8 by 19 mm (0.189 by 0.748 in).
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pins are not sheathed, in contrast to e.g.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This Danish standard plug is described in the Danish Plug Equipment Section 107-2-D1 Standard sheet (SRAF1962/DB 16/87 DN10A-R).
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Like in most European plugs, the power pins of Danish plugs are 19 mm (0.75 in) long and spaced 19 mm (0.75 in) apart, with a diameter of 4.8 mm (0.19 in).
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earthing pin is part of the plug (in contrast to French and Schuko plugs); it is D-shaped, 14 mm (0.55 in) long, and offset from the power pins by 13 mm (0.51 in).
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It is 4 mm (0.16 in) thick with a diameter of 6.5 mm (0.26 in).
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Danish standard provides for sockets to have child-resistant shutters.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are polarized in the same way as British ones: if earth is at the bottom, live is at the left of the socket.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Europlugs (CEE 7/16) and contour plugs (CEE 7/17) can safely be used with Danish sockets.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Physically the sockets also accept earthed CEE 7/4 (Schuko), CEE 7/6 (French), and CEE 7/7 (Schuko-French hybrid) plugs, but no earth connection will be established.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Therefore news sites and industry magazines warn that plugging these directly into a Type K socket can give noticeable electric shocks, be dangerous and even be life-threatening.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Traditionally all Danish sockets were equipped with a switch to prevent touching live pins when connecting/disconnecting the plug.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Today, sockets without switch are allowed, but they must be recessed to prevent touching the live pins.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since the early 1990s earthed sockets have been required in all new electric installations in Denmark.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older sockets need not be earthed, but all sockets, including old installations, must be protected by earth-fault interrupters by 1 July 2008.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A variation (standard DK 2-5a) of the Danish plug is for use only on surge protected computer sockets.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It fits into the corresponding computer socket and the normal socket, but normal plugs deliberately do not fit into the special computer socket.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug is often used in companies, but rarely in private homes.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There is another variation for hospital equipment with a rectangular left pin, which is used for life support equipment.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In 1986, the International Electrotechnical Commission published IEC 60906-1, a specification for a plug and socket that look similar, but are not identical, to the Swiss plug and socket.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This standard was intended to one day become common for all of Europe and other regions with 230 V mains, but the effort to adopt it as a European Union standard was put on hold in the mid-1990s.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug and socket are rated 16 A 250 V AC and are intended for use only on systems having nominal voltages between 200 V and 250 V AC.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug pins are 4.5 mm in diameter, live and neutral are on centres 19 mm apart.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The live pin is on the right when looking at a socket with the earth pin offset up.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shutters over the live and neutral pins are mandatory.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The first country to have officially adopted the standard is South Africa (as SANS 164-2).
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Paraguay has also adopted it as national standard (PNA-IEC 60906-1), but so far its application is voluntary, and as of March 2025, there is no indication that sockets of this type are commonly installed in the country.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Brazil developed a plug resembling IEC 60906-1 as the national standard under specification NBR 14136.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NBR 14136 standard has two versions, neither of which has pin dimensions or ratings complying with IEC 60906-1.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Use at 127 V is permitted by NBR 14136, which is against the intention of IEC 60906-1.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] South Africa adopted IEC 60906-1 as its national standard, SANS 164-2, in 1992.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard specifies both a 2-pin unearthed and 3-pin earthed plug system, equivalent to IEC Type N.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SANS 164-2 was designated the "preferred standard" in 2013, and South Africa is in the process of transitioning to it as the dominant system, expected to be completed by 2025 to 2035.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The SANS 164-2 system is compatible with the SANS 164-5 Europlug, commonly used in the country.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This transition aims to improve electrical safety and standardization, aligning South Africa with international plug and socket systems.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Brazil, which had been using mostly Europlugs as well as NEMA 1-15 and NEMA 5-15 plugs, adopted a (non-compliant) variant of IEC 60906-1 as the national standard in 1998 under specification NBR 14136 (revised in 2002).
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are used for both 220-volt and 127-volt regions of the country, despite the IEC 60906-2 recommendation that NEMA 5-15 be used for 120 V connections.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are two types of sockets and plugs in NBR 14136: one for 10 A, with a 4.0 mm pin diameter, and another for 20 A, with a 4.8 mm pin diameter.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This differs from IEC 60906-1 which specifies a pin diameter of 4.5 mm and a rating of 16 A.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NBR 14136 does not require shutters on the apertures, a further aspect of non-compliance with IEC 60906-1.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NBR 14136 was not enforced in that country until 2007, when its adoption was made optional for manufacturers.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Few private houses in Brazil have an earthed supply, so even if a three-pin socket is present it is not safe to assume that all three terminals are actually connected.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Most large domestic appliances were sold with the option to fit a flying earth tail to be locally earthed, but many consumers were unsure how to use this and so did not connect it.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The new standard has an earth pin, which in theory eliminates the need for the flying earth tail.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Due to their smaller pin diameter, Brazilian plugs rated for 10 A also fit into Brazilian sockets rated for 20 A and South African sockets rated for 16 A.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 20 A plugs do not fit into 10 A sockets, which is as intended.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, if the Brazilian and South African variants are mixed, due to receptacle tolerances it might be possible to insert a 16 A plug into a 10 A socket or a 20 A plug into a 16 A socket, which could overload the socket.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug defined in SI 32 (IS16A-R) is used only in Israel, the Gaza Strip and the West Bank.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are two versions: an older one with flat pins, and a newer one with round pins.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The pre-1989 system has three flat pins in a Y-shape, with live and neutral 19 mm (0.75 in) apart.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Pre-1989 sockets which accept only old-style plugs have become very rare in Israel.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets have a defined polarity; looking at the front, neutral is to the left, ground at the bottom, and live to the right.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Italian plugs and sockets are defined by the standard CEI 23-50 and referred to as "Type L".
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This includes models rated at 10 A and 16 A that differ in contact diameter and spacing.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both are symmetrical, allowing the live and neutral contacts to be inserted in either direction.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The 10 A plug has 4 mm diameter pins and the centres spaced 19 mm apart, while the 16 A plug has 5 mm diameter pins and the centres spaced 26 mm apart.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This plug type is also used in Chile and Uruguay.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Modern installations in Italy (and in other countries where Type L plugs are used) typically use sockets that accept several plug types.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The simplest type, designated CEI 23-50 P17/11, has a central round hole flanked by two figure-8 shaped holes, allowing the insertion of Italian 10 A and 16 A plugs as well as Europlugs.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These compact hybrid sockets are known as *presa bipasso* (twin-gauge socket).
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A larger, but more flexible hybrid socket is called CEI 23-50 P40.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It merges the *bipasso* form factor with a "Schuko" socket, thus also accepting earthed CEE 7/4 (Schuko) and CEE 7/7 (CEE hybrid) as well as unearthed CEE 7/17 ("contour") plugs.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Many appliances sold in Italy today are equipped with hybrid CEE 7/7 or CEE 7/17 plugs, but only these larger CEI 23-50 P40 sockets will accept them without an adapter.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, adaptors that allow plugging them into smaller sockets are also commonly sold and regulated by a specific standard.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Ordinary duplex socket mounted in ground-pin down orientation.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Most of North America and Central America, and some of South America, use connectors standardized by the National Electrical Manufacturers Association (NEMA).
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The devices are named using the format NEMA n-mmX, where *n* is an identifier for the configuration of pins and blades, *mm* is the maximum current rating, and *X* is either P for plug or R for receptacle.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] For example, NEMA 5-15R is a configuration type 5 receptacle supporting 15 A.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Corresponding *P* and *R* versions are designed to be mated.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Within the series, the arrangement and size of pins will differ, to prevent accidental mating of devices with a higher current draw than the receptacle can support.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NEMA-1 plugs have two parallel blades and are rated 15 A at 125 volts.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] They provide no ground connection but will fit into a grounding NEMA 5-15 receptacle.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Early versions were not polarized, but today most plugs are polarized via a wider neutral blade.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] (Unpolarized AC adaptors are a common exception.) Harvey Hubbell patented a parallel blade plug in 1913, where the blades were equal width (U.S. patent 1,064,833).
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In 1916 Hubbell received a patent for a polarized version where one blade was both longer and wider than the other (U.S. patent 1,180,648).
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In the polarized version of NEMA 1-15, introduced in the 1950s, both blades are the same length, with only the width varying.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Ungrounded NEMA-1 outlets are not permitted in new construction in the United States and Canada, but can still be found in older buildings.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NEMA 5-15 plug has two flat parallel blades like NEMA 1-15, and a ground (earth) pin.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The ground pin is longer than the live and neutral blades, such that an inserted plug connects to ground before power.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The ground hole is officially D-shaped, although some round holes exist and many plugs have round ground pins.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both current-carrying blades on grounding plugs may be narrow, since the ground pin enforces polarity, but outlets have a wider opening for the neutral blade to prevent ungrounded polarized plugs from being put in backwards.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This socket is recommended in IEC standard 60906-2 for 120-volt 60 Hz installations.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The National Electrical Contractors Association's installation standard (NEIS 130-2016) requires a consistent orientation for sockets installed together or nearby, but does not prescribe any specific orientation.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In practice, most sockets are mounted with the ground contact below the other contacts.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This ground-down orientation has been called the "sad socket", "dismayed face", or "shocked face" – names which reflect pareidolia.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Tamper-resistant sockets may be required in new residential construction, with shutters on the power blade sockets to prevent contact by objects inserted into the socket.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In stage lighting, this connector is sometimes known as *PBG* for *Parallel Blade with Ground*, *Edison* or *Hubbell*, the name of a common manufacturer.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The NEMA 5-20 AP variant has blades perpendicular to each other.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The receptacle has a T-slot for the neutral blade which accepts either 15 A parallel-blade plugs or 20 A plugs.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] NEMA 14-50 devices are frequently found in RV parks, since they are used for "shore power" connections of larger recreational vehicles.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also, it was formerly common to connect mobile homes to utility power via a 14-50 device.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Newer applications include Tesla's Mobile Connector for vehicle charging, which formally recommended the installation of a 14-50 receptacle for home use.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] 240 V 20-, 30- and 50-amp rated sockets are often used for high-current appliances such as air conditioners, clothes dryers and electric stoves, respectively.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Japanese Class II plug and socket appear physically identical to NEMA 1-15 and also carries 15 A.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The relevant Japanese Industrial Standards, JIS C 8303, imposes stricter dimensional requirements for the plug housing, different marking requirements, and mandatory testing and type approval.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older Japanese sockets and multi-plug adaptors are unpolarized—the slots in the sockets are the same size—and will accept only unpolarized plugs.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Japanese plugs generally fit into most North American sockets without modification, but polarized North American plugs may require adaptors or replacement non-polarized plugs to connect to older Japanese sockets.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Japan the voltage is 100 V, and the frequency is either 50 Hz (Eastern Japan: Tokyo, Yokohama, Tohoku, Kawasaki, Sapporo, Sendai and Hokkaido) or 60 Hz (Western Japan: Osaka, Kyoto, Nagoya, Shikoku, Kyushu and Hiroshima) depending on whether the customer is located on the Osaka or Tokyo grid.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Therefore, some North American devices which can be physically plugged into Japanese sockets may not function properly.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Japan also uses a grounded plug similar to the North American NEMA 5-15.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] However, it is less common than its NEMA 1-15 equivalent.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Since 2005, new Japanese homes are required to have class I grounded sockets for connecting domestic appliances.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This rule does not apply for sockets not intended to be used for domestic appliances, but it is strongly advised to have class I sockets throughout the home.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Swiss standard, also used in Liechtenstein, is *SN 441011* (*SN SEV 1011 until 2019) Plugs and socket-outlets for household and similar purposes*.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard defines a hierarchical system of plugs and sockets with two, three and five pins, and 10 A or 16 A ratings.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets will accept plugs with the same or fewer pins and the same or lower ratings.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard does not require the use of child protective shutters.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SN 441011 defines a "Type 1x" series of 10 A plugs and sockets.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 11 plug is unearthed, with two 4 mm diameter round pins spaced 19 mm apart.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 12 plug adds a central 4 mm diameter round earth pin, offset by 5 mm.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The obsolete type 12 socket had no recess, while the newer type 13 socket is recessed.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Both sockets will accept type 11 and type 12 plugs, and also the 2.5 A Europlug.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Earlier type 11 and 12 plugs had live and neutral pins without sleeved pins, which present a shock hazard when partially inserted into non-recessed sockets.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The IEC Type J designation refers to SEV 1011's type 12 plugs and type 13 sockets.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Unique to Switzerland is a three-phase power socket compatible with single-phase plugs: The type 15 plug has three round pins, of the same dimensions as type 12, plus two smaller flat rectangular pins for two additional power phases.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 15 socket is recessed, and has five openings (three round and two flat rectangular).
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] It will accept plugs of types 11, 12, 15 and the Europlug.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] SN 441011 also defines a "Type 2x" series of 16 A plugs and sockets.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] These are the same as their 10 A "Type 1x" counterparts, but replace the round pins with 4 mm × 5 mm rectangular pins.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The sockets will also accept "Type 1x" plugs.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The unearthed type 21 plug has two rectangular pins, with centres 19 mm apart.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 23 plug adds a central rectangular earth pin, offset by 5 mm.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recessed type 23 socket will accept plugs of types 11, 12, 21, 23 and the Europlug.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Again, the three-phase power socket is compatible with single-phase plugs, either of 10 A or 16 A ratings.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The type 25 plug has three rectangular pins of the same dimensions as type 23, plus two rectangular pins of the same dimensions as type 15.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The corresponding type 25 socket is recessed and will accept all Swiss plug types as well as the Europlug.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Thai Industrial Standard (TIS) 166-2547 and its subsequent update TIS 166-2549 replaced prior standards which were based on NEMA 1-15 and 5-15, as Thailand uses 230 V electricity.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plug has two round power pins 4.8 mm in diameter and 19 mm in length, insulated for 10 mm and spaced 19 mm apart, with an earthing pin of the same diameter and 21.4 mm in length, located 11.89 mm from the line connecting the two power pins.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The earth pin spacing corresponds to that of NEMA 5 and provides compatibility with prior hybrid three-pin sockets, which accept NEMA 1-15, NEMA 5-15, and Europlugs, all of which have been variably used in Thailand.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The standard also defines an ungrounded plug with a smaller form factor that is very similar to the Europlug (but a bit higher); its power pins are identical to the grounded variant and both are rated for up to 16 A (while the Europlug is only rated for 2.5 A).
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The generally used hybrid socket is also defined in TIS 166-2547, in addition to a plain three-round-pin socket, with plans to eventually replace the former and phase out support for NEMA-compatible plugs.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are polarized (as in NEMA 5-15).
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The grounded plug is similar to, but not interchangeable with, the Israeli SI32 plug.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Thai plug is designated as "Type O" at IEC World Plugs.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Special purpose sockets may be found in residential, industrial, commercial or institutional buildings.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Special-purpose sockets may be labelled or coloured to identify a reserved use of a system, or may have keys or specially shaped pins to prevent use of unintended equipment.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The plugs and sockets used to power electric stoves from a single-phase line have to be rated for greater current values than those used with three-phase supply because all the power has to be transferred through two contacts, not three.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] If not hardwired to the supply, electric stoves may be connected to the mains with an appropriate high power connector.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Some countries do not have wiring regulations for single-phase electric stoves.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Russia, an electric stove can often be seen connected with a 25, 32, or even 40 A connector.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In Norway, a 25 A grounded connector, rectangular shaped with rounded corners, is used for single-phase stoves.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The connector has three rectangular pins in a row, with the grounding pin longer than other two.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The corresponding socket is recessed to prevent shocks.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The Norwegian standard is NEK 502:2005 – standard sheet X (socket) and sheet XI (plug).
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] National wiring regulations sometimes prohibit the use of sockets adjacent to water taps, etc.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] A special socket, with an isolation transformer, may allow electric razors to be used near a sink.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Because the isolation transformer is of low rating, such outlets are not suitable to operate higher-powered appliances such as hair dryers.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] An IEC standard 61558-2-5, adopted by CENELEC and as a national standard in some countries, describes one type of shaver supply unit.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shaver sockets may accept multiple two-pin plug types including Australian (Type I) and BS 4573.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The isolation transformer often includes a 115 V output accepting two-pin US plugs (Type A).
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Shaver supply units must also be current limited, IEC 61558-2-5 specifies a minimum rating of 20 VA and maximum of 50 VA.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets are marked with a shaver symbol, and may also say "shavers only".
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Isolation transformers and dedicated NEMA 1-15 shaver receptacles were once standard installation practice in North America, but now a GFCI receptacle is used instead.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] This provides the full capacity of a standard receptacle but protects the user of a razor or other appliance from leakage current.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Though BS 4573 plugs look similar to Europlugs (Type C), there are subtle differences between them.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] While the BS 4573 plug has round 5 mm contacts, spaced at 16 mm, the Europlug has 4 mm contacts, spaced at (roughly) 19 mm.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] In order to insert a Europlug into a BS 4573 socket, an adaptor should be used.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Polarized plugs have a wider neutral blade; sockets accept both polarized and unpolarized plugs.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/17 specifies an unearthed hybrid plug that fits into both the CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are some CEE 7/17 plugs with special shape which are polarized when used with CEE 7/5 sockets (mechanically only).
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recess provided by CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets offers protection against touching the live pins of CEE 7/4, CEE 7/6, CEE 7/7, and CEE 7/17 plugs.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] When used in CEE 7/1 (unearthed) sockets or "universal adaptors" there is no protection for those plugs.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/1 socket accepts earthed CEE 7/3, CEE 7/5 and CEE 7/7 plugs but provides no earth connection.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Older sockets can have a very shallow recess.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] BS 4573 and BS EN 61558-2-5 do not explicitly specify a current rating for a compliant plug, see BS 4573 section of British and compatible standards.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] CEE 7/7 specifies an earthed hybrid plug that fits into both the CEE 7/3 and CEE 7/5 sockets.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Plug can only be inserted one way with French CEE 7/5, but lack of wiring convention means that the system is not polarized.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The actual rating of non-rewirable plugs is marked according to the fuse fitted by the cord set manufacturer, the fuse rating being determined by the rating of the flexible cable.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also accepts unearthed Class II plugs that include an unwired dummy earth pin.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Except when used with unearthed plugs such as the Europlug.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets may be recessed by 8.3 mm, but few are.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are unearthed Class II plugs with an unwired dummy earth pin, accepted by all sockets.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] There are also unearthed Class II plugs without an earth pin, accepted only by sockets that do not have an earth-pin-driven shutter.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Import of plugs with non-partially-insulated pins no longer allowed after 2012.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Unrecessed type 12 sockets may no longer be installed since 2017.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] The recess provided by some Danish sockets offers protection against touching the live pins of plugs.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Sockets must be recessed or equipped with a switch that allows them to be turned off.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Type L comes in two variations with ratings of 10 A and 16 A having different pin diameters and spacing from each other.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p02] Also used in Paraguay (PNA-IEC 60906-1).
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Italian bypass lampholder plugs with Edison screw mount.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] A lampholder plug fits into a light socket in place of a light bulb to connect appliances to lighting circuits.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Where a lower rate was applied to electric power used for lighting circuits, lampholder plugs enabled the consumers to reduce their electricity costs.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Edison screw lampholder adaptors (for NEMA 1-15 plugs) are still commonly used in the Americas.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This Soviet plug, now rarely used, has pin dimensions and spacing equal to the Europlug, but lacks the insulation sleeves.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] It has a round body like the European CEE 7/2 or flat body with a round base like CEE 7/17.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The pins are parallel and do not converge.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The body is made of fire-resistant thermoset plastic.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The corresponding 6 A socket accepts the Europlug, but not others as the 4.5 mm holes are too small to accept the 4.8 mm pins of CEE 7/4, CEE 7/6 or CEE 7/7 plugs.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] There were also moulded rubber plugs available for devices up to 16 A similar to CEE 7/17, but with a round base without any notches.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They could be altered to fit a CEE 7/5 or CEE 7/3 socket by cutting notches with a sharp knife.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Some appliances sold in the Soviet Union had a flat unearthed plug with an additional pass-through socket on the top, allowing a stacked arrangement of plugs.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The pins of the secondary plug (which lacked insulation sleeves) could not be inserted into the cylindrical sockets completely, leaving a 5 mm gap between the primary and secondary plugs.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The adaptors were mostly used for low power appliances (for example, connecting both a table lamp and a radio to a socket).
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Compared to the standard BS 1363 plugs found in the UK, each pin is rotated 90 degrees.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This style of plug/socket was used by university laboratories (from batteries) and the BBC, and is still in use in parts of the London Underground for 110 V AC voltage supply.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In the 1960s they were used for 240 V DC in the Power laboratory of the Electrical Engineering department of what was then University College, Cardiff.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Power was supplied by the public 240 V DC mains which remained available in addition to the 240 V AC mains until circa 1969, and thereafter from in-house rectifiers.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They were also used in the Ministry of Defence Main Building inside circuits powered from the standby generators to stop staff from plugging in unauthorized devices.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] They were also known to be used in some British Rail offices for the same reason.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In the 1960s, Italian firm BTicino introduced an alternative to the Europlug or CEI 23-16 connectors then in use, called Magic Security.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The socket is rectangular with lateral key pins and indentations to maintain polarization and prevent insertion of a plug with different current ratings.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Three single-phase general purpose connectors were rated 10 A, 16 A and 20 A; and a three-phase industrial connector rated 10 A; all of them have different key-pin positioning so plugs and sockets cannot be mismatched.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The socket is closed by a safety lid (bearing the word *Magic* on it) which can be opened only with an even pressure on its surface, thus preventing the insertion of objects (except the plug itself) inside the socket.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The contacts are positioned on both sides of the plug; the plug is energised only when it is inserted fully into the socket.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The system is not compatible with Italian CEI plugs, nor with Europlugs.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Appliances were never sold fitted with these security plugs, and the use of adaptors would defeat the safety features, so the supplied plugs had to be cut off and replaced with the security connector.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Even so, the *Magic* security system had some success at first because its enhanced safety features appealed to customers; standard connectors of the day were not considered safe enough.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The decline of the system occurred when safety lids similar to the Magic type were developed for standard sockets.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Italy, the system was never definitively abandoned.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Though very rarely seen today, it is still marked as available in BTicino's catalogue, (except for the three-phase version, which stopped being produced in July 2011).
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Chile, 10 A Magic connectors are commonly used for computer/laboratory power networks, as well as for communications or data equipment.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] This allows delicate electronics equipment to be connected to an independent circuit breaker, usually including a surge protector or an uninterruptible power supply backup.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] The different style of plug makes it more difficult for office workers to connect computer equipment to a standard unprotected power line, or to overload the UPS by connecting other office appliances.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] In Iceland, Magic plugs were widely used in homes and businesses alongside Europlug and Schuko installations.
[src:iec-60320/ac-power-plugs-and-sockets-p03] Their installation in new homes was still quite common even in the late 1980s.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] AES3 was jointly developed by the Audio Engineering Society (AES) and the European Broadcasting Union (EBU) and so is also known as **AES/EBU**.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] The standard was first published in 1985 and was revised in 1992 and 2003.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] AES3 has been incorporated into the International Electrotechnical Commission's standard **IEC 60958**, and is available in a consumer-grade variant known as S/PDIF.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] The development of standards for digital audio interconnect for both professional and domestic audio equipment, began in the late 1970s in a joint effort between the Audio Engineering Society and the European Broadcasting Union, and culminated in the publishing of AES3 in 1985.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] The AES3 standard has been revised in 1992 and 2003 and is published in AES and EBU versions.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] Early on, the standard was frequently known as AES/EBU.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] Variants using different physical connections are specified in IEC 60958.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] These are essentially consumer versions of AES3 for use within the domestic high fidelity environment using connectors more commonly found in the consumer market.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] These variants are commonly known as S/PDIF.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] The AES3 standard parallels part 4 of the international standard IEC 60958.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] Of the physical interconnection types defined by IEC 60958, two are in common use.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] Type I connections use balanced, three-conductor, 110-ohm twisted pair cabling with XLR connectors.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] Type I connections are most often used in professional installations and are considered the standard connector for AES3.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] The hardware interface is usually implemented using RS-422 line drivers and receivers.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] IEC 60958 Type II defines an unbalanced electrical or optical interface for consumer electronics applications.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] The precursor of the IEC 60958 Type II specification was the Sony/Philips Digital Interface, or S/PDIF.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] Both were based on the original AES/EBU work.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] S/PDIF and AES3 are interchangeable at the protocol level, but at the physical level, they specify different electrical signalling levels and impedances, which may be significant in some applications.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] AES/EBU signals can also be run using unbalanced BNC connectors with a 75-ohm coaxial cable.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] The unbalanced version has a very long transmission distance as opposed to the 150 meters maximum for the balanced version.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] The AES-3id standard defines a 75-ohm BNC electrical variant of AES3.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] This uses the same cabling, patching and infrastructure as analogue or digital video, and is thus common in the broadcast industry.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] The low-level protocol for data transmission in AES3 and S/PDIF is largely identical, and the following discussion applies for S/PDIF, except as noted.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] AES3 was designed primarily to support stereo PCM encoded audio in either DAT format at 48 kHz or CD format at 44.1 kHz.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] No attempt was made to use a carrier able to support both rates; instead, AES3 allows the data to be run at *any* rate, and encoding the clock and the data together using biphase mark code (BMC).
[src:iec-60320/aes3] Each audio sample (of up to 24 bits) is combined with four flag bits and a synchronisation preamble which is four time slots long to make a *subframe* of 32 time slots.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] Two subframes (A and B, normally used for left and right audio channels) make a **frame**.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] Frames contain 64 bit periods and are produced once per audio sample period.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] At the highest level, each 192 consecutive frames are grouped into an *audio block*.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] While samples repeat each frame time, metadata is only transmitted once per audio block.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] At 48 kHz sample rate, there are 250 audio blocks per second, and 3,072,000 time slots per second supported by a 6.144 MHz biphase clock.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] The synchronisation preamble is a specially coded *preamble* that identifies the subframe and its position within the audio block.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] Preambles are not normal BMC-encoded data bits, although they do still have zero DC bias.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] The three preambles are called X, Y, Z in the AES3 standard; and M, W, B in IEC 958 (an AES extension).
[src:iec-60320/aes3] The 8-bit preambles are transmitted in the time allocated to the first four time slots of each subframe (time slots 0 to 3).
[src:iec-60320/aes3] Any of the three marks the beginning of a subframe.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] X or Z marks the beginning of a frame, and Z marks the beginning of an audio block.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] In two-channel AES3, the preambles form a pattern of ZYXYXYXY..., but it is straightforward to extend this structure to additional channels (more subframes per frame), each with a Y preamble, as is done in the MADI protocol.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] There is one channel status bit in each subframe, a total of 192 bits or 24 bytes for each channel in each block.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] Between the AES3 and S/PDIF standards, the contents of the 192-bit channel status word differ significantly, although they agree that the first channel status bit distinguishes between the two.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] In the case of AES3, the standard describes, in detail, the function of each bit.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] SMPTE timecode data can be embedded within AES3 signals.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] It can be used for synchronization and for logging and identifying audio content.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] It is embedded as a 32-bit binary word in bytes 18 to 21 of the channel status data.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] The AES11 standard provides information on the synchronization of digital audio structures.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] the AES52 standard describes how to insert unique identifiers into an AES3 bit stream.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] SMPTE 2110-31 defines how to encapsulate an AES3 data stream in Real-time Transport Protocol packets for transmission over an IP network using the SMPTE 2110 IP based multicast framework.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] SMPTE 302M-2007 defines how to encapsulate an AES3 data stream in an MPEG transport stream for television applications.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] AES3 digital audio format can also be carried over an Asynchronous Transfer Mode network.
[src:iec-60320/aes3] The standard for packing AES3 frames into ATM cells is AES47.
[src:iec-60320/aes47] The Audio Engineering Society (AES) published AES47 in 2002.
[src:iec-60320/aes47] The method described by AES47 is also published by the International Electrotechnical Commission as **IEC 62365**.
[src:iec-60320/aes47] Many professional audio systems are now combined with telecommunication and IT technologies to provide new functionality, flexibility and connectivity over both local and wide area networks.
[src:iec-60320/aes47] AES47 was developed to provide a standardised method of transporting the standard digital audio per AES3 over telecommunications networks that provide a quality of service required by many professional low-latency live audio uses.
[src:iec-60320/aes47] AES47 may be used directly between specialist audio devices or in combination with telecommunication and computer equipment with suitable network interfaces.
[src:iec-60320/aes47] In both cases, AES47 the same physical structured cable used as standard by the telecommunications networks.
[src:iec-60320/aes47] Common network protocols like Ethernet use large packet sizes, which produce a larger minimum latency.
[src:iec-60320/aes47] Asynchronous transfer mode divides data into 48-byte *cells* which provide lower latency.
[src:iec-60320/aes47] The original work was carried out at the British Broadcasting Corporation’s R&D department and published as "White Paper 074", which established that this approach provides the necessary performance for professional media production.
[src:iec-60320/aes47] AES47 was originally published in 2002 and was republished with minor revisions in February 2006.
[src:iec-60320/aes47] Amendment 1 to AES47 was published in February 2009, adding code points in the ATM Adaptation Layer Parameters Information Element to signal that the time to which each audio sample relates can be identified as specified in AES53.
[src:iec-60320/aes47] The change in thinking from traditional ATM network design is not to necessarily use ATM to pass IP traffic (apart from management traffic) but to use AES47 in parallel with standard Ethernet structures to deal with extremely high performance secure media streams.
[src:iec-60320/aes47] AES47 has been developed to allow the simultaneous transport and switched distribution of a large number of AES3 linear audio streams at different sample frequencies.
[src:iec-60320/aes47] AES47 can support any of the standard AES3 sample rates and word size.
[src:iec-60320/aes47] AES11 Annex D (the November 2005 printing or version of AES11-2003) shows an example method to provide isochronous timing relationships for distributed AES3 structures over asynchronous networks such as AES47 where reference signals may be locked to common timing sources such as GPS.
[src:iec-60320/aes47] AES53 specifies how timing markers within AES47 can be used to associate an absolute time stamp with individual audio samples as described in AES47 Amendment 1.
[src:iec-60320/aes47] An additional standard has been published by the Audio Engineering Society to extend AES3 digital audio carried as AES47 streams to enable this to be transported over standard physical Ethernet hardware.
[src:iec-60320/aes47] This additional standard is known as AES51-2006.
[src:iec-60320/aes47] For minimum latency, AES47 uses "raw" ATM cells, ATM adaptation layer 0.
[src:iec-60320/aes47] Each ATM virtual circuit negotiates the parameters of a stream at connection time.
[src:iec-60320/aes47] In addition to the same rate and number of channels (which may be more than the 2 supported by AES3), the negotiation covers the number of bits per sample and the presence of an optional data byte.
[src:iec-60320/aes47] The total must be 1, 2, 3, 4 or 6 bytes per sample, so it evenly divides the ATM cell size.
[src:iec-60320/aes47] AES3 uses 4 bytes per sample (24 bits of sample plus the optional data byte), but AES47 supports additional formats.
[src:iec-60320/aes47] The optional data byte contains four "ancillary" bits corresponding to the AES3 VUCP bits.
[src:iec-60320/aes47] However, the P (parity) bit is replaced by a B bit which is set on the first sample of each audio block, and clear at all other times.
[src:iec-60320/aes47] This serves the same function as the B (or Z) synchronization preamble.
[src:iec-60320/aes47] The other half of the data byte contains three "data protection" bits for error control and a sequencing bit.
[src:iec-60320/aes47] The concatenation of the sequencing bits from all samples in a cell (combined little-endian) form a sequencing word of 8, 12, 16, or 24 bits.
[src:iec-60320/aes47] The first four bits of the sequencing word are a sequencing number, used to detect dropped cells.
[src:iec-60320/aes47] This increments by 1 for each cell transmitted.
[src:iec-60320/aes47] The second four bits are for error detection, with bit 7 being an even parity bit for the first byte.
[src:iec-60320/aes47] The third four bits, if present, are a second sequencing number which can be used to align multiple virtual circuits.
[src:iec-60320/aes47] This standard may be studied by downloading a copy of the latest version from the AES standards web site as AES53-2018.
[src:iec-60320/ansi] The **American National Standards Institute** (**ANSI**) is a private nonprofit organization that oversees the development of voluntary consensus standards for products, services, processes, systems, and personnel in the United States.
[src:iec-60320/ansi] The organization also coordinates U.S. standards with international standards so that American products can be used worldwide.
[src:iec-60320/ansi] ANSI accredits standards that are developed by representatives of other standards organizations, government agencies, consumer groups, companies, and others.
[src:iec-60320/ansi] These standards ensure that the characteristics and performance of products are consistent, that people use the same definitions and terms, and that products are tested the same way.
[src:iec-60320/ansi] ANSI also accredits standards developing organizations (SDOs) and provides a searchable directory of accredited standards developers (ASDs).
[src:iec-60320/ansi] ANSI similarly accredits organizations that carry out product or personnel certification in accordance with requirements defined in international standards.
[src:iec-60320/ansi] The organization's headquarters are in Washington, D.C.
[src:iec-60320/ansi] ANSI's operations office is located in New York City.
[src:iec-60320/ansi] The ANSI annual operating budget is funded by the sale of publications, membership dues and fees, accreditation services, fee-based programs, and international standards programs.
[src:iec-60320/ansi] Many ANSI regulations are incorporated by reference into United States federal statutes (i.e. by OSHA regulations referring to individual ANSI specifications).
[src:iec-60320/ansi] ANSI does not make these standards publicly available, and charges money for access to these documents; it further claims that it is copyright infringement for them to be provided to the public by others free of charge.
[src:iec-60320/ansi] These assertions have been the subject of criticism and litigation.
[src:iec-60320/ansi] ANSI was most likely formed in 1918, when five engineering societies and three government agencies founded the **American Engineering Standards Committee** (**AESC**).
[src:iec-60320/ansi] In 1928, the AESC became the **American Standards Association** (**ASA**).
[src:iec-60320/ansi] In 1966, the ASA was reorganized and became the **United States of America Standards Institute** (**USASI**).
[src:iec-60320/ansi] In February 1969, Ralph Nader harshly criticized the USASI in public remarks as "manifestly deceptive" in several different ways.
[src:iec-60320/ansi] He specifically attacked the name USASI as improperly implying some kind of official connection with the federal government of the United States.
[src:iec-60320/ansi] had been members of the United Engineering Society (UES).
[src:iec-60320/ansi] At the behest of the AIEE, they invited the U.S. government Departments of War, Navy (combined in 1947 to become the Department of Defense or DOD) and Commerce to join in founding a national standards organization.
[src:iec-60320/ansi] According to Adam Stanton, the first permanent secretary and head of staff in 1919, AESC started as an ambitious program and little else.
[src:iec-60320/ansi] Staff for the first year consisted of one executive, Clifford B.
[src:iec-60320/ansi] LePage, who was on loan from a founding member, ASME.
[src:iec-60320/ansi] An annual budget of $7,500 was provided by the founding bodies.
[src:iec-60320/ansi] In 1931, the organization (renamed ASA in 1928) became affiliated with the U.S.
[src:iec-60320/ansi] National Committee of the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), which had been formed in 1904 to develop electrical and electronics standards.
[src:iec-60320/ansi] ANSI's members are government agencies, organizations, academic and international bodies, and individuals.
[src:iec-60320/ansi] In total, the Institute represents the interests of more than 270,000 companies and organizations and 30 million professionals worldwide.
[src:iec-60320/ansi] ANSI's market-driven, decentralized approach has been criticized in comparison with more planned and organized international approaches to standardization.
[src:iec-60320/ansi] Although ANSI itself does not develop standards, the Institute oversees the development and use of standards by accrediting the procedures of standards developing organizations.
[src:iec-60320/ansi] ANSI accreditation signifies that the procedures used by standards developing organizations meet the institute's requirements for openness, balance, consensus, and due process.
[src:iec-60320/ansi] ANSI also designates specific standards as American National Standards, or ANS, when the Institute determines that the standards were developed in an environment that is equitable, accessible and responsive to the requirements of various stakeholders.
[src:iec-60320/ansi] Voluntary consensus standards quicken the market acceptance of products while making clear how to improve the safety of those products for the protection of consumers.
[src:iec-60320/ansi] There are approximately 9,500 American National Standards that carry the ANSI designation.
[src:iec-60320/ansi] The institute is the official U.S. representative to the two major international standards organizations, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO), as a founding member, and the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), via the U.S.
[src:iec-60320/ansi] ANSI participates in almost the entire technical program of both the ISO and the IEC, and administers many key committees and subgroups.
[src:iec-60320/ansi] In many instances, U.S. standards are taken forward to ISO and IEC, through ANSI or the USNC, where they are adopted in whole or in part as international standards.
[src:iec-60320/ansi] Adoption of ISO and IEC standards as American standards increased from 0.2% in 1986 to 15.5% in May 2012.
[src:iec-60320/ansi] Each of the panels works to identify, coordinate, and harmonize voluntary standards relevant to these areas.
[src:iec-60320/ansi] In 2009, ANSI and the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) formed the Nuclear Energy Standards Coordination Collaborative (NESCC).
[src:iec-60320/ansi] NESCC is a joint initiative to identify and respond to the current need for standards in the nuclear industry.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Non-rewirable plugs and connectors are typically permanently molded onto cords and cannot be removed or rewired without cutting the cords.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] The standard uses the terms "male" and "female" only for individual pins and socket contacts, but in general usage they are also applied to the complete plugs and connectors.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] "Connectors" and "appliance outlets" are fitted with socket contacts, and "appliance inlets" and "plug connectors" are fitted with pin contacts.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Each type of coupler is identified by a standard sheet number.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] For appliance couplers this consists of the letter "C" followed by a number, where the standard sheet for the appliance inlet is 1 higher than the sheet for the corresponding cable connector.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Many types of coupler also have common names.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] The most common ones are "IEC connector" for the common C13 and C14, the "figure-8 connector" for C7 and C8, and "cloverleaf connector" or "Mickey Mouse connector" for the C5/C6.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Detachable appliance couplers are used in office equipment, measuring instruments, IT environments, and medical devices, among many types of equipment for worldwide distribution.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Each appliance's power system must be adapted to the different plugs used in different regions.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] An appliance with a permanently-attached plug for use in one country cannot be readily sold in another which uses an incompatible wall socket; this requires keeping track of variations throughout the product's life cycle from assembly and testing to shipping and repairs.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Instead, a country-specific power supply cord can be included in the product packaging, so that model variations are minimized and factory testing is simplified.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] A cord which is fitted with non-rewireable (usually moulded) connectors at both ends is termed a *cord set*.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Appliance manufacturing may be simplified by mounting an appliance coupler directly on the printed circuit board.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Assembly and handling of an appliance is easier if the power cord can be removed without much effort.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Appliances can be used in another country easily, with a simple change of the power supply cord (including a connector and a country-specific plug).
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] The power supply cord can be replaced easily if damaged, because it is a standardized part that can be unplugged and re-inserted.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Safety hazards, maintenance expenditure and repairs are minimized.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] The standards define the mechanical, electrical and thermal requirements and safety goals of power couplers.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] The standard scope is limited to appliance couplers with a rated voltage not exceeding 250 V (a.c.) at 50 Hz or 60 Hz, and a rated current not exceeding 16 A.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Further sub-parts of IEC 60320 focus on special topics such as protection ratings and appliance specific requirements.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Selection of a coupler depends in part on the IEC appliance classes.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] The shape and dimensions of appliance inlets and connectors are coordinated so that a connector with lower current rating, temperature rating, or polarization cannot be inserted into an appliance inlet that requires higher ratings.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] (i.e. a Protection Class II connector cannot mate with a Class I inlet which requires an earth); whereas connecting a Class I connector to a Class II appliance inlet is possible because it creates no safety hazard.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Pin temperature is measured where the pin projects from the engagement surface.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] The maximum permitted pin temperatures, are 70 °C (158 °F), 120 °C (248 °F), and 155 °C (311 °F), respectively (the higher temperatures are not applicable to interconnection couplers).
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] The pin temperature is determined by the design of the appliance, and its interior temperature, rather than by its ambient temperature.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Typical applications with increased pin temperatures include appliances with heating coils such as ovens or electric grills.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] It is generally possible to use a connector with a higher rated temperature with a lower rated appliance inlet, but the keying feature of the inlet prevents use of a connector with a lower temperature rating.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Connectors are also classified according to the method of connecting the cord, either as rewirable connectors or non-rewirable connectors.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] In addition the standards define further general criteria such as withdrawal forces, testing procedures, the minimum number of insertion cycles, and the number of flexings of cords.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] IEC 60320-1 defines a *cord set* as an "assembly consisting of one cable or cord fitted with one plug and one connector, intended for the connection of an electrical appliance or equipment to the electrical supply".
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] It also defines an *interconnection cord set* as an "assembly consisting of one cable or cord fitted with one plug connector and one connector, intended for the interconnection between two electrical appliances".
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] In addition to the connections within the standards, as mentioned, there are possible combinations between appliance couplers and IEC interconnection couplers.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Fitted with a flexible cord, the components become interconnection cords to be used for connecting appliances or for extending other interconnection cords or power supply cords.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] North American rating agencies (CSA, NOM-ANCE, and UL) will certify IEC 60320 connectors for higher currents than are specified in the IEC standard itself.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] In May 2011, the modified criteria were codified as **UL 60320-1** and **CSA C22.2 no.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] 60320-1**, respectively, with compliance required from May 2021.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Given the 120 V (±5%) mains supply used in the United States and Canada, these higher ratings permit devices with C6 and C8 inlets to draw more than 114 V × 2.5 A = 285 W from the mains, and devices with C14 inlets to draw more than 1140 W from the mains.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] This is exploited by high-powered computer power supplies, up to 1200 W output, and even some particularly efficient 1500 W output models to use the more popular C14 inlet on products sold worldwide.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Although less common, power bricks with C6 and C8 inlets and ratings up to 300 W also exist.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] The dimensions and tolerances for connectors, appliance inlets, appliance outlets and plug connectors are given in standard sheets, which are dimensioned drawings showing the features required for safety and interchangeability.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Found on many electric shavers, for example.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Similar connector to C5/C6, but with a key ridge instead of an earthing conductor, withdrawn from standard.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Commonly referred to as a "clover-leaf" or "Mickey Mouse" connector due to its shape.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Domestic audio, video, radio equipment and doubly insulated power supplies.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] C8 inlet is 10 mm deep, C8A and C8B inlets are 15.5 mm deep.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Commonly referred to as "figure 8" or "infinity" in the UK.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] for many older models of their hi-fi equipment (for example, A76, A77, A78, B77, B225).
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Similar to C9 with a slot in the connector, withdrawn from standard.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Very common on personal computers and peripherals.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] but C13/14 connectors are only rated for 70 °C (158 °F): a device such as a kettle requires the C15/16 connector, rated for 120 °C (248 °F).
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] For use in high-temperature settings (for example, electric kettle).
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Also sometimes used for enterprise IT equipment if the possibility exists that the temperature at the socket reaches more than 70 degrees.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Similar to C15/C16, but the top is narrowed to exclude the C15 cord connector.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] , datacenter rack-mounted power-distribution units and other equipment that draws too much current for C13/C14 type to be used.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] The mains appliance couplers are all engineered to connect an appliance via a power cord to mains power.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] The C1 coupler and C2 inlet were commonly used for mains-powered electric shavers.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] These have largely been supplanted by cordless shavers with rechargeable batteries or corded shavers with an AC adapter.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] This coupler is sometimes colloquially called a "cloverleaf" or "Mickey Mouse" coupler (because the cross section resembles the silhouette of the Disney character).
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] The C6 inlet is used on laptop power supplies as well as on some desktop computers, some LCD monitors, and some desktop label printers.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Commonly known as a "figure-8", "infinity" or "shotgun" connector due to the shape of its cross-section, or less commonly, a Telefunken connector after its originator.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] This coupler is often used for small cassette recorders, battery/mains-operated radios, battery chargers, some full-size audio-visual equipment, laptop computer power supplies, video game consoles, and similar double-insulated appliances.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] A C8B inlet type is defined by the standard for use by dual-voltage appliances; it has three pins and can hold a C7 connector in either of two positions, allowing the user to select voltage by choosing the position the connector is inserted.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] A similar but polarized connector has been made, but is not part of the standard.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] This connector could be found on the US/Canada models of Sony PlayStation and PS2.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Sometimes called C7P, it is asymmetrical, with one side squared.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Unpolarized C7 connectors can be inserted into the polarized inlets; however, doing so might be a safety risk if the device is designed for polarized power.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Although not specified by IEC 60320, and not clear whether any formal written standard exists, the most common wiring appears to connect the rounded side to the hot (live) line, and the squared to the neutral.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Apple uses a modified version of the C7 connector for their power adapters.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] On the power adapter itself, a separate metal slide-on connector exists to both help secure the connection with the wall adapter or cable, as well as provide a ground connection on for the AC adapter end.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] The design of the power adapter also allows for standard C7 connectors to be used in non-grounded applications.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] An early example of a product that uses this connector is the Apple II.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] A power cord with a suitable power plug (for the locality where the appliance is being used) on one end and a C13 connector (connecting to the appliance) on the other is commonly called an *IEC cord*.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] There are also a variety of splitter blocks, splitter cables, and similar devices available.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] These are usually un-fused (with the exception of C13 cords attached to BS 1363 plugs, which are always fused).
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] A cable consisting of a C13 and an E interconnection connector is commonly mislabeled as an "extension cord", as although that is not the intended purpose, it can be used as such.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] They are also commonly mislabeled as C14 instead of E.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] The C13 connector and C14 inlet are also commonly found on servers, routers, and switches.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Power cord sets utilizing a C13 connector and an E interconnection plug are commonplace in data centers to provide power from a power distribution unit (PDU) to a server.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Some electric kettles and similar hot household appliances like home stills use a supply cord with a C15 connector and a matching C16 inlet on the appliance; their temperature rating is 120 °C (248 °F) rather than the 70 °C (158 °F) of the similar C13/C14 combination.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] The official designation in Europe for the C15/C16 coupler is a "hot-condition" coupler.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] These are similar in form to the C13/C14 coupler, except with a ridge opposite the earth in the C16 inlet (preventing a C13 fitting), and a corresponding valley in the C15 connector (which doesn't prevent it fitting a C14 inlet).
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] For example, an electric kettle cord can be used to power a computer, but an unmodified computer cord cannot be used to power a kettle.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] There is some public confusion between C13/C14 and C15/C16 couplers, and it is not uncommon for C13/C14 to be informally referred to as "kettle plug" or "kettle lead" (or some local equivalent).
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] In European countries the C15/C16 coupler has replaced and made obsolete the formerly common types of national appliance coupler in many applications.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] This modification of the C15/C16 coupler has an even higher 155 °C (311 °F) temperature rating.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Similar to C13/C14 coupler, but unearthed.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] A C18 inlet accepts a C13 connector, but a C14 inlet does not accept a C17 connector.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] The IBM Wheelwriter series of electronic typewriters are one common application.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Three-wire cords with C13 connectors, which are easier to find, are sometimes used in place of the two-wire cords for replacement.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] In this case, the ground wire will not be connected.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] The C17/C18 coupler is often used in audio applications where a floating ground is maintained to eliminate hum caused by ground loops.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Other common applications are the power supplies of Xbox 360 game consoles, replacing the C15/C16 coupler employed initially, some PlayStation 4 Pro models, and large CRT televisions manufactured by RCA in the early 1990s.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] This connector can also be found on high-current medical and scientific equipment.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] It is rectangular and has pins parallel to the long axis of the coupler face.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Interconnection couplers are similar to appliance couplers, but with the gender roles reversed.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Specifically, the female appliance outlet is built into a piece of equipment, while the male plug connector is attached to a cord.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] They are identified by letters, not numbers, with one letter identifying the plug connector, and the alphabetical next letter identifying the mating appliance outlet.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] For example, an E plug fits into an F outlet.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Beginning with an amendment published in 2022, three of the commonly used high temperature variants have been standardized as types M–R.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Cables with a C13 connector at one end and a type E plug connector at the other are commonly available.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Type J outlets are used in a similar way.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] C3, C4, C11 and C12 standard sheets are no longer listed in the standard.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Standard sheet C25 shows retaining device dimensions.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Sheet C26 shows detail dimensions for pillar-type terminals, where the end of the screw bears on a wire directly or through a pressure plate.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Sheet 27 shows details for screw terminals, where the wire is held by wrapping it around the head of a screw.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] IEC 60320-3 specifies the standard sheets as well as the corresponding gauges (go/no-go gauges) used for verifying the dimensional compliance of connectors, appliance inlets, plug connectors and appliance outlets.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] Gauges are typically manufactured from hardened stainless steel (e.g., hardness ≥ 60 HRC) and supplied with traceable calibration reports.
[src:iec-60320/iec-60320] The standard defines specific gauges corresponding to each standard sheet (such as those for C1, C5, C7, C13, C14, C15, C16 series and others), including dedicated deformation test gauges and contact depth gauges.
